WEBVTT
Kind: captions
Language: en

00:00:00.080 --> 00:00:03.860
- The following is a conversation with Irving
Finkel, who is a scholar of ancient languages.

00:00:03.960 --> 00:00:11.720
He's a curator at the British Museum for over 45 years,
and is a much admired and respected world expert.

00:00:11.780 --> 00:00:19.330
He's an expert on cuneiform script and more generally, on
ancient languages like Sumerian, Akkadian, and Babylonian.

00:00:19.380 --> 00:00:27.330
He's also an expert on ancient board games,
Mesopotamia magic, medicine, literature, and culture.

00:00:27.460 --> 00:00:34.980
I should also mention that both on and off the mic,
Irving was a super kind and fun person to talk to.

00:00:35.040 --> 00:00:41.780
He has an infectious enthusiasm for ancient history that
of course I already love, but fell in love with even more.

00:00:41.800 --> 00:00:45.700
This is the Lex Fridman Podcast. To support it,
please check out our sponsors in the description.

00:00:45.720 --> 00:00:49.600
You can also find links to contact me,
ask questions, get feedback, and so on.

00:00:49.640 --> 00:00:56.150
And now, dear friends,
here's Irving Finkel.

00:00:56.740 --> 00:01:00.580
Where and when did writing
originate in human civilization?

00:01:00.620 --> 00:01:05.280
Let's go back a few thousand years.

00:01:05.300 --> 00:01:09.020
- The first attempts at writing that we could call
writing go back to the middle of the fourth millennium,

00:01:09.220 --> 00:01:16.240
say around 3500 BC, something like that.

00:01:16.260 --> 00:01:20.200
There were people in the Middle East, individuals
who lived between the Euphrates and Tigris Rivers.

00:01:20.220 --> 00:01:23.950
They had clay as their operating material for
building and all sorts of other purposes.

00:01:24.040 --> 00:01:31.860
Eventually, as a writing support, they somehow developed the idea
of the basis of writing, which means that you can make a sign.

00:01:31.920 --> 00:01:40.040
People agree on it, on a surface that another person,
when they see it, they know what sound it engenders.

00:01:40.080 --> 00:01:47.900
That is the essence of writing, that there's an agreed
system of symbols that A can use and B can then play back,

00:01:47.960 --> 00:01:51.560
either in their heads or literally with their
voices, a bit like a gramophone record.

00:01:51.660 --> 00:02:02.660
So, when it really began is a terribly, terribly awkward question for us,
because the truth of the matter is, we have no idea when anything began.

00:02:02.700 --> 00:02:13.540
All we can say is that the oldest evidence we have is around 3500 BC, but
whether that was anywhere near the time or the stage when this started off

00:02:13.620 --> 00:02:25.160
for the first time seems to me very, very unlikely. So, among
these Mesopotamians around 3500, they started to do this.

00:02:25.240 --> 00:02:29.100
They made up signs which everybody understood and
they could write simple pictographic messages.

00:02:29.140 --> 00:02:41.100
Foot is a foot, leg is a leg, and barley is barley. Then very, very
gradually, they had the idea of how you could represent numerals.

00:02:41.140 --> 00:02:49.120
They also had the idea that the pictures could also represent sounds,
and once they had the idea that you could write sounds with pictures,

00:02:49.180 --> 00:02:53.130
that's the crucial thing, that a picture of a foot not only
meant foot, but it meant the sound of the word for foot.

00:02:53.130 --> 00:03:04.140
Once this happened, some probably very, very imaginative and clever persons
had a kind of light bulb moment when they realized that they could develop

00:03:04.200 --> 00:03:13.980
a whole panoply of signs which could convey sound. And once
you had that, you're liberated from pictographic writing

00:03:15.140 --> 00:03:22.680
into a position where you can record language.
So language, grammar, and all the rest of it,

00:03:23.720 --> 00:03:27.640
and before long, proverbs and literature, and
all the other things that got written down.

00:03:27.700 --> 00:03:35.660
So it was a pretty gigantic step whenever it was taken,
but we really have no idea when it was first taken.

00:03:35.680 --> 00:03:43.100
But the first evidence we have presents a sort of clear-ish picture.
It was simple and it got more complicated, then it became magnificent.

00:03:43.120 --> 00:03:51.020
So that with all the signs, a fluent, well-trained
scribe could not only write down the Sumerian language,

00:03:51.060 --> 00:04:00.960
which was one of the native tongues of Iraq, or the Babylonian language, which
was the other main language of Iraq, but also any other language he heard.

00:04:02.080 --> 00:04:05.500
if somebody came speaking
French ahead of their time and

00:04:05.780 --> 00:04:09.720
spoke out loud, he could record
with these signs the sound of

00:04:09.800 --> 00:04:13.760
French. And we have examples of
funny languages in the world

00:04:13.840 --> 00:04:17.320
around in the Bronze Age, which
were written in cuneiform purely by

00:04:17.399 --> 00:04:20.860
ear. And often sometimes
the scribes who recorded by

00:04:20.899 --> 00:04:24.720
dictation or by something, wrote
stuff they couldn't understand,

00:04:24.760 --> 00:04:28.600
but somebody else could read and
understand it. So, what you have

00:04:28.680 --> 00:04:35.860
is long before the alphabet, when the
alphabet was not even a dream, a complex,

00:04:35.880 --> 00:04:39.300
bewildering-looking, off-putting writing
system, which was actually very beautiful, very

00:04:39.380 --> 00:04:43.040
flexible, and lasted for
well over three millennia,

00:04:43.080 --> 00:04:46.900
probably closer to four millennia. And
it took a long time for the alphabet,

00:04:46.940 --> 00:04:50.600
which anybody would say was much, much
more useful and much more sensible, to

00:04:50.620 --> 00:04:57.730
displace it. So it's one of the major
stages of man's intellect, because quite

00:04:57.960 --> 00:05:04.840
soon after writing first took off,
the signs began to proliferate

00:05:05.460 --> 00:05:09.360
and someone said, "Hey, we haven't got a sign for
this sound," or, "We haven't got a sign for this

00:05:09.480 --> 00:05:15.900
idea." And so it began to swell
out. And at some extremely

00:05:16.000 --> 00:05:19.760
remarkable stage, one,
probably only one person

00:05:19.880 --> 00:05:23.720
suddenly realized that
if there was no control,

00:05:23.800 --> 00:05:27.570
they would grow exponentially
until it was all

00:05:27.600 --> 00:05:31.070
nonsense and everybody had their own writing. And
the second thing is that no one could remember

00:05:31.100 --> 00:05:34.740
them unless they were written down
in a retrievable way. So they

00:05:34.800 --> 00:05:38.620
invented not only writing,
they invented lexicography,

00:05:38.660 --> 00:05:42.200
which means that early in the
third millennium, they put down

00:05:42.340 --> 00:05:46.140
all the things that were made of wood
and all the things that were made of

00:05:46.200 --> 00:05:50.180
reeds and all the names of colors and of countries
and all the gods and everything. They made a

00:05:50.220 --> 00:05:56.940
systematic attempt to standardize
these signs and to make them

00:05:56.980 --> 00:06:00.390
retrievable, and of course
to teach them. And having

00:06:00.440 --> 00:06:04.200
exercised that rigor from
the outset, it meant

00:06:04.270 --> 00:06:08.123
that the thing became
streamlined and stayed

00:06:08.504 --> 00:06:12.123
more or less as it was all the way
through, for three millennia or

00:06:12.284 --> 00:06:16.274
more. Because the stamp
put on it by those early

00:06:16.564 --> 00:06:20.544
visionaries, not only who came up
with the system and how it would

00:06:20.644 --> 00:06:24.004
work, but to preserve it
and to safeguard it, was

00:06:24.424 --> 00:06:27.944
fantastically effective. So, it
means that there were scholars in

00:06:27.964 --> 00:06:31.904
Babylon in the third century or the
second century, when Alexander was

00:06:31.944 --> 00:06:35.683
there, for example. If somebody dug
up a tablet in very early writing,

00:06:36.324 --> 00:06:40.044
they would have a pretty good idea what it meant. They
would recognize the signs, even though they were so

00:06:40.124 --> 00:06:43.524
ancient, and they'd see the relationships
between them. So, you have a

00:06:43.944 --> 00:06:49.944
fantastically strong system
where the spinal cord

00:06:50.904 --> 00:06:54.854
was structured in a
lexicographic, regular system.

00:06:54.884 --> 00:06:58.664
So, lexicography and
what the signs were was

00:06:58.724 --> 00:07:04.764
jealously safeguarded and protected,
and it lasted fantastically.

00:07:04.804 --> 00:07:10.344
- We should say that the name of that system
that lasted for 3,000 years is cuneiform.

00:07:10.404 --> 00:07:13.904
- Yeah. So, in the 19th century, about 1840,

00:07:13.943 --> 00:07:17.683
1850, they started to find
these things on excavations in

00:07:17.744 --> 00:07:21.524
Iraq, the big Assyrian cities
and sometimes further south,

00:07:21.544 --> 00:07:25.344
the Babylonian cities. They found
these clay tablets, which in the

00:07:25.404 --> 00:07:28.844
ground lasted unimaginable lengths of

00:07:28.964 --> 00:07:32.834
time. And they were all written in
what we call cuneiform script. And

00:07:33.164 --> 00:07:37.084
the cuneiform part of
it means wedge-shaped,

00:07:37.124 --> 00:07:41.063
because cuneus in Latin means
wedge. And when they first saw

00:07:41.144 --> 00:07:45.084
these signs, they realized
that a cluster of marks

00:07:45.604 --> 00:07:49.204
broke down into different arrangements

00:07:49.304 --> 00:07:53.104
of triangular shapes. And it's
most clear on the Assyrian

00:07:53.264 --> 00:07:56.784
reliefs, where the writing is
very big and you can easily

00:07:56.844 --> 00:08:00.404
tell that they were that shape. On
a tablet, the wedge is not quite so

00:08:00.504 --> 00:08:04.424
predominant. So, that was it. So,
they first called them cuneatic

00:08:04.524 --> 00:08:08.324
or cuneiform, and the word
stuck. And of course,

00:08:09.004 --> 00:08:12.943
growing up in the British Museum and reading
these things for a living becomes a kind of

00:08:14.404 --> 00:08:18.084
lifetime's work to make sure that everybody
in the country knows what cuneiform means.

00:08:18.124 --> 00:08:21.304
Because once in a while you meet somebody who
never heard of the word at all, and this is

00:08:21.323 --> 00:08:25.264
appalling. So, people do
survive, however. But it's an

00:08:25.304 --> 00:08:29.104
important mission because such
an achievement by man and

00:08:29.323 --> 00:08:33.223
so much knowledge was encapsulated in

00:08:33.264 --> 00:08:37.104
these lumps of clay, because they
used it for everyday things like

00:08:37.223 --> 00:08:41.063
letters and business documents and
contracts. This is one thing. And then the

00:08:41.144 --> 00:08:41.764
kings wrote

00:08:43.084 --> 00:08:47.024
long, elaborate accounts of their campaigns
and their military activities. And

00:08:47.064 --> 00:08:51.144
then there was proper literature,
history, and magic and medicine and

00:08:53.184 --> 00:08:57.064
all other genres of literature
that we would naturally list on a

00:08:57.104 --> 00:09:00.784
sheet of paper in alphabetic
writing, what you would use writing

00:09:00.824 --> 00:09:04.144
for. They basically did.
And it had the unexpected

00:09:04.204 --> 00:09:08.124
quality that most of these clay
things lasted in the ground

00:09:08.444 --> 00:09:12.244
until now. So, however many hundreds of

00:09:12.304 --> 00:09:15.964
thousands of tablets are in the world's
museums and collections, there must be

00:09:16.064 --> 00:09:19.664
millions of them in the
ground awaiting excavation.

00:09:19.704 --> 00:09:26.104
So, in a way that's a comforting thought,
'cause they're safe there and protected.

00:09:26.124 --> 00:09:29.824
- You said that the development
of cuneiform, of these

00:09:29.904 --> 00:09:33.804
tablets, of written language is
one of the greatest, probably

00:09:33.944 --> 00:09:37.804
the greatest invention in
human history. How hard do

00:09:37.864 --> 00:09:41.264
you think it was to come up
with this? And we should make

00:09:41.344 --> 00:09:47.483
clear that that very specific
element of encoding sound

00:09:49.444 --> 00:09:53.164
on the tablet, that's the genius
invention. Drawing a picture makes

00:09:53.223 --> 00:09:57.144
sense. Okay, here's, you
know, barley. Here's the

00:09:57.204 --> 00:10:00.384
sun. Here's whatever, the actual object.

00:10:00.424 --> 00:10:00.944
- Exactly.

00:10:00.964 --> 00:10:05.584
- But to actually write down
sound is a genius invention.

00:10:05.624 --> 00:10:09.244
- Well, I think it's rather
paradoxical, because the first

00:10:09.444 --> 00:10:13.004
generation or so of tablets that we
have are written in these pictographic

00:10:13.104 --> 00:10:16.964
signs where each sign means
what it looks like. So, this

00:10:17.024 --> 00:10:20.923
is a very limited method of
recording messages, and it

00:10:20.983 --> 00:10:24.923
doesn't lend itself to recording
grammar. And then the secondary phase,

00:10:24.964 --> 00:10:28.864
as we understand it from archeology,
is the perception that you

00:10:28.904 --> 00:10:32.864
could take these signs, still
meaning what they look like but also

00:10:32.904 --> 00:10:36.723
what the words sounded like. So,
then you have all these wonderful

00:10:36.844 --> 00:10:40.723
ice cubes which express all the
sounds of the language from which you

00:10:40.764 --> 00:10:44.223
can record words and, and
grammar and everything

00:10:44.284 --> 00:10:47.973
else. Now, the thing is,
the received law from

00:10:48.024 --> 00:10:51.714
Assyriology is it was that way round, that

00:10:51.784 --> 00:10:55.324
first we had pictures and
secondly we had sound.

00:10:55.364 --> 00:10:59.024
Well, I have to say, I
find this very hard to

00:10:59.064 --> 00:11:03.044
believe, because if you
had a group of people

00:11:03.124 --> 00:11:09.964
in an environment where it was compellingly
necessary to make a system that you made

00:11:09.983 --> 00:11:13.624
marks on a surface which everybody
could understand and use,

00:11:13.743 --> 00:11:17.243
why wouldn't you start
out with signs that made

00:11:17.644 --> 00:11:21.464
sounds? Because everybody speaks
the same language, right? So

00:11:21.564 --> 00:11:25.524
you... they didn't have A, B, C, D,
E, F, G, but they could easily work

00:11:25.624 --> 00:11:29.334
out all the vowels and consonants
without naming them as

00:11:29.334 --> 00:11:32.584
vowels and consonants, but they're
component parts. So, they could have had

00:11:32.723 --> 00:11:36.654
signs that started out... Because
if you decided you had...

00:11:36.684 --> 00:11:40.604
We have 26, let's say they had
50 signs that would create the

00:11:40.644 --> 00:11:44.614
sound, they could write anything
without any further trouble. So, I

00:11:44.644 --> 00:11:47.864
find it very bewildering that
they started off with the least

00:11:47.944 --> 00:11:51.704
flexible and the least adaptable system

00:11:51.764 --> 00:11:55.564
of pictographs, and then they moved
on to the sound. I don't know why

00:11:55.604 --> 00:11:59.051
they bothered with it.
And my hunch is that the

00:11:59.112 --> 00:12:02.411
archeological evidence that we
have on this score is ultimately

00:12:02.452 --> 00:12:06.252
misleading, because I think
this, that probably for a

00:12:06.311 --> 00:12:09.931
very, very long time before
the Sumerians, people in the

00:12:10.051 --> 00:12:13.531
world, the world of what we
call the Middle East, were in

00:12:13.572 --> 00:12:17.291
contact, they traded, they probably
even had wars, and they had

00:12:17.332 --> 00:12:21.212
messages between them. And I think
there was a long running system of

00:12:21.252 --> 00:12:26.492
communication between people
who didn't share a language.

00:12:27.512 --> 00:12:31.232
for whom pictures would
suffice. So, if merchants come

00:12:31.551 --> 00:12:34.891
and they have three sheep to
sell, so they draw three little

00:12:34.952 --> 00:12:38.801
sheep. You know how much it is
and what they are and so forth.

00:12:38.832 --> 00:12:42.681
And so I think that what happened
with the Sumerians, with their

00:12:42.752 --> 00:12:50.071
pictographic signs, is that those signs
are right at the end of a very, very, very

00:12:50.132 --> 00:12:53.931
long period of time, when
somebody thought, "What we

00:12:54.031 --> 00:13:00.651
can do is take these stupid inhibited
no smoking signs and write language."

00:13:00.661 --> 00:13:04.232
That is what I think happened.
That's what I think happened.

00:13:04.271 --> 00:13:05.692
- Is this a controversial statement?

00:13:05.732 --> 00:13:12.311
- Highly controversial. Many
Assyriologists would leave the room.

00:13:12.332 --> 00:13:16.151
But I'm not scared of controversy because
it's natural. I mean, if you think

00:13:16.232 --> 00:13:18.212
about it, it's natural because

00:13:19.911 --> 00:13:23.571
you don't have to have an alphabet
to divide your word into sounds,

00:13:24.232 --> 00:13:28.051
see? For example, in
Sumerian, you have a funny

00:13:28.151 --> 00:13:32.132
system of writing, you have a root, like
du, which means to go. And then you

00:13:32.171 --> 00:13:35.551
have prefixes, like E or Mu or

00:13:35.592 --> 00:13:39.452
Ba, and one's a passive, one's an active,
and this and this. So when you have a

00:13:39.492 --> 00:13:43.411
sentence, you have one of
the Mu, Ba, or E prefixes,

00:13:43.452 --> 00:13:46.712
then you have the root, and then you
have things at the end. So it is called

00:13:46.752 --> 00:13:50.391
agglutinative by people who like to make
things look more important than they are.

00:13:50.411 --> 00:13:54.391
So you have the central thing, you slap stuff on
the beginning, slap stuff on the end, and each

00:13:54.452 --> 00:13:58.291
particle creates a bit of meaning. So you
have a long verb which tells you, "He

00:13:58.311 --> 00:14:01.811
would've done it if he could, but he
couldn't," kind of thing, in the form of the

00:14:01.852 --> 00:14:05.692
verb. But the thing is, if you wanted to write
down, you and I decided to write down, so the first

00:14:05.702 --> 00:14:09.531
thing we would do is have a
sign Mu, and then we'd have Ba,

00:14:09.911 --> 00:14:15.391
and then we'd have E, because every
five minutes people made those noises.

00:14:15.632 --> 00:14:16.531
You see what I mean?

00:14:16.612 --> 00:14:23.752
- Yeah, absolutely. Do you think it's
possible we might find much, much older--

00:14:23.852 --> 00:14:24.112
- I do

00:14:24.132 --> 00:14:26.252
- ... cuneiform type tablets?

00:14:26.311 --> 00:14:30.061
- Or, or pictographic type tablets,
before the cuneiform and

00:14:30.071 --> 00:14:32.202
it's drawing type, and I'll tell you why.

00:14:32.512 --> 00:14:36.012
Because there's this marvelous site
in Turkey called Gobekli Tepe.

00:14:36.051 --> 00:14:36.382
- Oh yeah?

00:14:36.382 --> 00:14:37.281
- Do you know about Gobekli Tepe?

00:14:37.291 --> 00:14:37.842
- Yes, of course.

00:14:37.872 --> 00:14:41.241
- Well, everybody knows about
the buildings and the

00:14:41.331 --> 00:14:45.271
architecture and the... everybody
knows about it. If you go

00:14:45.411 --> 00:14:49.171
all the way through the photographs,
which the archaeologists unwisely

00:14:49.252 --> 00:14:53.212
put online, you will find
in the middle of one color

00:14:53.271 --> 00:14:57.092
plate with lots of other things,
a round green stone like a

00:14:57.171 --> 00:15:00.531
scarab from Egypt. That's to say,
it has an arched back and a flat

00:15:00.651 --> 00:15:04.331
bottom. And on the flat bottom, there
are hieroglyphic signs carved in the

00:15:04.411 --> 00:15:08.112
stone, right? No one said
anything about it at

00:15:08.252 --> 00:15:15.551
all, but it's clear to me, A, that this was a stamp to ratify
where the carvings of the signs on clay or some other sealing

00:15:15.671 --> 00:15:19.212
carvings of the signs on
clay or some other sealing

00:15:19.271 --> 00:15:26.811
material would leave an impression. It
must be that. So this is about 9000 BC.

00:15:26.852 --> 00:15:30.732
Now when I was a boy at university
my professor said to me that

00:15:30.811 --> 00:15:34.712
the reason writing evolved in
Mesopotamia, because they had

00:15:34.771 --> 00:15:38.592
complex cities with ziggurats
and big buildings and lots of

00:15:38.651 --> 00:15:42.641
people and they had to organize everything,
and so they invented writing to cope with

00:15:42.651 --> 00:15:46.291
it. Well, if they had to
cope with that in Sumer in

00:15:46.571 --> 00:15:49.932
3000 BC, they sure as hell
had to do it at Gobekli

00:15:50.012 --> 00:15:54.442
Tepe because they've hardly even begun
to finish excavating the sites of-

00:15:54.472 --> 00:15:58.012
... Gobekli Tepe. They go on and
on like Manchester and Newcastle

00:15:58.232 --> 00:16:05.712
United. And really the old rule would be
you could not have architecture like that,

00:16:06.452 --> 00:16:10.432
that... without the... planned and
built according to principle with all

00:16:10.452 --> 00:16:14.112
the different people. You couldn't
have that without writing in southern

00:16:14.212 --> 00:16:17.791
Iraq. So how come
suddenly then 7,000 years

00:16:17.831 --> 00:16:20.972
earlier, they do it there?
That, and that green stone

00:16:21.531 --> 00:16:25.212
shows that they had writing.
That was an official who

00:16:25.311 --> 00:16:29.291
sealed this, got the stuff or whatever
it was, or it was his dad's name

00:16:29.352 --> 00:16:32.952
or whatever it is, got a wiggly
snake and a wiggly this. That is

00:16:32.972 --> 00:16:36.752
pictographic writing. Maybe even as
phonetic writing, I don't know, but it

00:16:36.811 --> 00:16:40.432
was writing thousands of years before

00:16:40.852 --> 00:16:44.492
in the south. And that's what I think
it is. You know, people came with

00:16:44.612 --> 00:16:48.571
metal from, or precious stones
from Anatolia. They knew that

00:16:48.632 --> 00:16:51.811
in the south they had lots and lots of
stuff, they wanted to trade, they had to

00:16:51.872 --> 00:16:55.212
communicate. And it's
basically like having a

00:16:55.271 --> 00:16:59.100
cigarette with an X through the middle.
Everybody in the world knows what

00:16:59.151 --> 00:17:02.732
that means. They don't know what the word
for cigarette is in this language or

00:17:02.811 --> 00:17:06.541
cancer or filter or tobacco,
it doesn't matter. That's

00:17:06.571 --> 00:17:10.231
pictographic writing.
We still use it. And,

00:17:10.551 --> 00:17:14.492
and it's, it's, it's above all kinds of
mess. And I think that was the prevailing

00:17:14.571 --> 00:17:18.452
system because I honestly believe
that the people at this time were

00:17:18.492 --> 00:17:22.382
not stupid. They weren't gorillas.
They weren't less advanced than

00:17:22.411 --> 00:17:25.992
we are. They were probably
indistinguishable from what we are. So you

00:17:26.071 --> 00:17:29.911
have merchants and wanderers and
people who say, "Let's go down the

00:17:29.952 --> 00:17:33.742
river and see where we end up." And
people looking for money, looking for

00:17:33.752 --> 00:17:37.422
women, looking for everything. I mean, and
that's surely how it was. But if you look at

00:17:37.492 --> 00:17:40.272
those Gobekli buildings with a skeptical

00:17:40.472 --> 00:17:44.411
eye, how it could be. I
mean, the finish of it is

00:17:44.452 --> 00:17:48.081
astonishing, the structure of
it, the vision of it. So the

00:17:48.252 --> 00:17:52.091
workforce and the tools
and the organization, you

00:17:52.132 --> 00:17:55.732
know, what did they do it with? A megaphone?
"Your breakfast!" And all that kind of stuff.

00:17:55.792 --> 00:17:57.572
No way. No way.

00:17:57.591 --> 00:17:59.341
- So that's a really
controversial statement that...

00:17:59.341 --> 00:18:00.182
- It is really controversial

00:18:00.192 --> 00:18:04.022
- ...at the time of Gobekli Tepe, there
may have been already a writing system.

00:18:04.052 --> 00:18:07.891
- There was, because the thing
is about it, that it's a seal

00:18:08.052 --> 00:18:12.048
to ratify... it's not just a
squiggle on a pot and you can

00:18:12.088 --> 00:18:15.988
say, "Oh, that's just a piece of..." This
is a finished thing with a flat surface.

00:18:16.028 --> 00:18:19.808
You press it down, so you have some contract,
you have some building arrangement,

00:18:19.848 --> 00:18:23.568
some... that we're paying for these
bricks, whatever it was. And the official

00:18:23.628 --> 00:18:27.498
person had to squash it down and it
leaves the impression. I mean, I am

00:18:27.548 --> 00:18:30.428
a great believer in Sherlock Holmes...

00:18:30.608 --> 00:18:34.278
...as a teaching system for
intelligence and rationality

00:18:34.548 --> 00:18:38.068
and logic in thinking. I read those
stories a million times when I was a kid,

00:18:38.508 --> 00:18:42.268
and the thing about them, one of the things
which impresses me most of all, was this

00:18:42.288 --> 00:18:46.108
point quoted by Holmes, not
original to him, that it is

00:18:46.128 --> 00:18:52.488
theoretically possible to infer
the Niagara Falls from a raindrop.

00:18:52.528 --> 00:18:54.797
- That's a powerful statement. Yeah.

00:18:54.828 --> 00:18:58.297
- It's a powerful statement. Well,
that seal from Gobekli Tepe is a

00:18:58.328 --> 00:19:02.238
raindrop from which I infer writing, and

00:19:02.268 --> 00:19:06.238
it's perfectly possible they all wrote on
flat leaves. After all, in many parts of

00:19:06.268 --> 00:19:09.687
the world, that's what happened. So
for example, in the Indus Valley,

00:19:09.728 --> 00:19:13.578
people write the most abject
nonsense about the Indus

00:19:13.668 --> 00:19:16.568
Valley writing system,
but all we have is seals,

00:19:16.608 --> 00:19:20.488
basically. So they are also for
ratification purposes, and they

00:19:20.548 --> 00:19:24.447
have the name of the owner in three
or four or maybe five signs, and

00:19:24.467 --> 00:19:31.388
it's probably me, son of my dad, or milkman
or whatever it is. And it's obvious,

00:19:31.467 --> 00:19:35.248
it's obvious that they had
writing on a perishable material.

00:19:35.268 --> 00:19:39.068
They can't just have had inscribed stone

00:19:39.328 --> 00:19:43.088
seals, and many parts
of India today write on

00:19:43.148 --> 00:19:47.128
palm leaf. Why should it be any different?
So people think, you know, "Oh, well,

00:19:47.187 --> 00:19:50.748
just 'cause it's now, it wouldn't be
then." But actually, that argument is

00:19:50.828 --> 00:19:54.228
utterly, utterly fallacious,
because the process of

00:19:54.288 --> 00:19:57.818
evolution is stymied left,
right, and center by

00:19:57.848 --> 00:20:01.628
inertia. Inertia is nearly as strong as

00:20:01.707 --> 00:20:05.138
evolution, and this is something
that the people who talk about

00:20:05.228 --> 00:20:07.748
progress and ideas have no idea about.

00:20:07.768 --> 00:20:11.318
- First of all, your whole line of work,
you're making me realize, is a kind of

00:20:11.348 --> 00:20:15.048
like Sherlock Holmes type of process.

00:20:15.068 --> 00:20:18.978
The deciphering of the
language, archeology, of taking

00:20:18.987 --> 00:20:22.648
those pieces of evidence and trying
to reconstruct a vision of that

00:20:22.748 --> 00:20:29.808
world, and now you're making me realize
that even all the cuneiform tablets we

00:20:29.868 --> 00:20:39.748
have is just a raindrop compared to the
waterfall of thousands of years of humans.

00:20:39.758 --> 00:20:43.588
- Yes, we have a lot, but it's nothing
in comparison with what existed.

00:20:43.648 --> 00:20:47.288
But not only that. See, we don't have
to decipher anymore. We can read

00:20:47.408 --> 00:20:51.228
Akkadian or Babylonian, Sumerian
pretty well fluently. That's not a

00:20:51.248 --> 00:20:54.848
problem. So the information
which you can get from these

00:20:54.888 --> 00:20:58.397
sources, especially three millennia
of sources, is very, very

00:20:58.508 --> 00:21:06.158
substantial. Very substantial, but it means
that Assyriologists have the in-built

00:21:06.348 --> 00:21:10.258
idea that what we have is something
like all there ever was, which is

00:21:10.308 --> 00:21:13.978
absurd. For example, there's
a period called the Ur III

00:21:14.308 --> 00:21:18.128
Period, where people lived
in city-states. They wrote

00:21:18.168 --> 00:21:21.768
very small account tablets by the
thousand, and there were two or three

00:21:21.888 --> 00:21:26.487
major cities where this is the way
they lived. People had to bring

00:21:27.428 --> 00:21:31.408
tithes and offerings, and everything
was recorded by what I always refer to

00:21:31.508 --> 00:21:35.048
and people sympathize with is the
ancestors of the Inland Revenue, because

00:21:35.148 --> 00:21:38.978
everything had to be written down so
that some schmuck could check it and

00:21:39.088 --> 00:21:42.868
fill out the ledger, and some other schmuck
above him could okay it, so there's no

00:21:42.947 --> 00:21:46.868
funny business or no mistakes. Now, the
thing is, there are thousands of those

00:21:46.908 --> 00:21:54.428
tablets written in about 2100 to 2000 BC,
thousands of them, about the size of a

00:21:54.487 --> 00:21:57.987
box of matches. So people
like to generalize about the

00:21:58.048 --> 00:22:05.168
Sumerians at this time of the world, but
they probably all came out of two rooms,

00:22:07.008 --> 00:22:10.947
because they were dumped when they
were no longer needed in some kind

00:22:11.008 --> 00:22:14.617
of room, and the archeologists in the 19th
century came down on these, and then all the

00:22:14.617 --> 00:22:18.588
locals came and they dug them up and they sold
them all over the place, and they've gone all

00:22:18.648 --> 00:22:22.378
over the world. Thousands and
thousands of them, out of probably two

00:22:22.447 --> 00:22:26.288
storage rooms, which is not
a whole culture or a whole

00:22:26.348 --> 00:22:32.687
country, or their whole history, or their
belief systems. So our view of it is

00:22:32.908 --> 00:22:36.648
skewed by the nature of the
material, and sometimes the

00:22:36.687 --> 00:22:40.028
material is opulent and
benevolent, but not

00:22:40.128 --> 00:22:43.768
always, and sometimes the
people who work with skewed

00:22:43.808 --> 00:22:47.678
material don't even realize
how skewed it is. I

00:22:47.768 --> 00:22:50.437
mean, you know, it's quite remarkable.

00:22:50.487 --> 00:22:53.608
- So you, in all your time
of studying cuneiform

00:22:53.708 --> 00:22:56.467
tablets, do you sometimes late at night

00:22:57.308 --> 00:23:00.928
get a glimpse of the waterfall?
Like, can you imagine?

00:23:01.008 --> 00:23:04.748
- Yes. I can imagine. I can
imagine easily, because

00:23:05.128 --> 00:23:08.768
once in a while, a library is
discovered. In the 1850s at

00:23:08.828 --> 00:23:12.687
Nineveh, which was the Assyrian
capital, there was a great king,

00:23:12.748 --> 00:23:16.128
king of the world, called
Ashurbanipal, and he had a

00:23:16.148 --> 00:23:20.088
fantastic library and he promoted
it. He impounded tablets,

00:23:20.148 --> 00:23:24.008
he had them brought to Nineveh. He
wanted all the prevailing knowledge and

00:23:24.028 --> 00:23:27.187
all knowledge from before under
one roof. It was kind of like

00:23:27.268 --> 00:23:31.187
an Alexandria thing. So he was
a trained scholar, and this

00:23:31.228 --> 00:23:34.967
is what he did, and they found it
in the 19th century. They dug it

00:23:35.068 --> 00:23:38.888
up, Layard and those people. So what
did they find? They found the tablets

00:23:38.928 --> 00:23:42.888
higgledy-piggledy all over the floor
of a huge room and in the corridors

00:23:42.928 --> 00:23:47.128
and everything- ...and lots of them
broken and lots of them burnt.

00:23:48.687 --> 00:23:52.328
So ever since then, until
really quite recently,

00:23:53.568 --> 00:23:57.548
Assyriologists who spent all their... Well,
people who work on these Nineveh tablets

00:23:57.588 --> 00:24:01.568
spent all their time joining the bits
together, and you have the story about

00:24:01.608 --> 00:24:05.338
Gilgamesh and the goddess who falls in
love with him in the garden, and she wants

00:24:05.368 --> 00:24:07.158
to seduce him, and you can't find the bit.
So you look for another bit and you look

00:24:07.168 --> 00:24:11.148
for another bit. And gradually, they piece
together the literature, and the assumption

00:24:11.168 --> 00:24:14.172
has always been that if you put them all
together again, you'll have the whole library.

00:24:14.192 --> 00:24:18.152
But it's the absolute opposite, because
what happened was that the Babylonians in

00:24:18.192 --> 00:24:20.552
the south, in my opinion,

00:24:21.812 --> 00:24:25.802
they worked hand-in-glove with the
Elamites from Iran. They had a pincer

00:24:25.831 --> 00:24:29.732
movement, and they beat Assyria, they
conquered Assyria. And they ran through

00:24:29.771 --> 00:24:33.412
the capital and they set fire to everything.
Pinched all the women and took all the

00:24:34.272 --> 00:24:38.252
jewelry and all the gold. And people say
that in a fit of pique, they destroyed

00:24:38.292 --> 00:24:42.252
the library. But they wouldn't destroy
the library because it was the giant

00:24:42.331 --> 00:24:45.992
brain from which the Assyrians ran
a world empire, and it had all the

00:24:46.032 --> 00:24:49.572
knowledge in the world. They
destroyed that? They spoke the same

00:24:49.632 --> 00:24:52.852
language, they had the same writing
system. They'd have taken them

00:24:53.152 --> 00:25:00.831
all safely home, cart after cart after
cart. And I think what's left there is

00:25:00.872 --> 00:25:04.492
duplicates and broken things, the things
that got dropped and everything, and that's

00:25:04.552 --> 00:25:05.852
everyone thinks is it.

00:25:06.652 --> 00:25:06.831
- Oh.

00:25:06.852 --> 00:25:09.212
- So this is also uncontroversial.
It's a controversial point.

00:25:09.232 --> 00:25:10.432
- You're just nonstop-

00:25:10.452 --> 00:25:10.722
- But it's common-

00:25:10.722 --> 00:25:11.572
- ...starting trouble.

00:25:11.581 --> 00:25:12.581
- It's common sense. It's common-

00:25:12.592 --> 00:25:14.712
- You're going to get both
of us canceled today.

00:25:14.812 --> 00:25:18.712
- But you see the thing. It's predicated on

00:25:18.752 --> 00:25:22.612
the assumption that what we
have is what there... only what

00:25:22.652 --> 00:25:26.272
there was. And this is such
a fallacy. It needs to be

00:25:26.872 --> 00:25:29.292
attacked left, right, and center.

00:25:29.352 --> 00:25:34.932
- So, a lot of the cuneiform
language is already deciphered.

00:25:34.992 --> 00:25:38.952
Can you speak to the deciphering
process? How hard is it?

00:25:38.972 --> 00:25:42.952
Maybe take us to this place of for

00:25:43.052 --> 00:25:46.732
you yourself first learning
a language. Figuring out the

00:25:46.812 --> 00:25:50.652
puzzle of it. How does it
feel? How does it look like

00:25:50.732 --> 00:25:54.372
to a brain that doesn't deeply understand
it? And how do you then piece stuff

00:25:54.432 --> 00:25:58.292
together? Maybe you can go
to the early days. Sort of

00:25:58.392 --> 00:26:01.032
the Rosetta Stone of cuneiform also.

00:26:01.092 --> 00:26:04.952
- That's important. Well, the first thing is,
is that how the cuneiform writing system

00:26:04.992 --> 00:26:08.952
works, because the crucial
point, once you see

00:26:09.012 --> 00:26:13.232
it, it makes a lot of things clear,
is that they wrote in syllables.

00:26:14.172 --> 00:26:18.122
So, if you take the English alphabet,
which of course they didn't, you have

00:26:18.152 --> 00:26:22.072
the letter B, G, D, P, H, and so

00:26:22.172 --> 00:26:25.752
forth. They couldn't write a
consonant. They couldn't do

00:26:25.792 --> 00:26:29.012
that. So, what they did is
they had a vowel before a

00:26:29.052 --> 00:26:34.012
consonant or one after.
Say you have Ab and Ba.

00:26:34.831 --> 00:26:42.112
But as they had four vowels, you had to have
Ab and Ba, Ib and Bi, Ub and Bu, Eb and

00:26:42.212 --> 00:26:47.152
Be. So you had the range of things
clustered around what we call a consonant.

00:26:47.192 --> 00:26:50.872
So they had all those for all the
letters, which gave them a basic

00:26:51.012 --> 00:26:54.831
system. There was much more to it than that,
and it was more complicated than that.

00:26:54.851 --> 00:26:58.772
Well, we don't have to really go into it,
but basically if you are a Babylonian

00:26:59.452 --> 00:27:03.331
and you want to write the word museum,
which of course is one of the most

00:27:03.351 --> 00:27:07.272
important words in the English language
and other languages too. So what you would

00:27:07.312 --> 00:27:09.772
do is you would write the syllable "mu"-

00:27:09.952 --> 00:27:13.092
...and then the sign "Z"
and then the sign "um".

00:27:13.892 --> 00:27:17.622
So you split the word up into its component
syllables. When you read it in your

00:27:17.712 --> 00:27:21.432
mind, you squash them together
into museum. That's the

00:27:21.472 --> 00:27:25.432
basic system. They had other
signs which gave you a clue as

00:27:25.472 --> 00:27:31.412
to the meaning and the bits around the
edge. But it's basically syllabic writing.

00:27:31.452 --> 00:27:34.632
So, when you go to university
to study cuneiform,

00:27:36.152 --> 00:27:39.372
what you have to learn is all the signs

00:27:40.092 --> 00:27:44.012
and all their values,
because unfortunately they

00:27:44.022 --> 00:27:47.812
didn't just have one for each,
they had multiple ones. And the

00:27:47.872 --> 00:27:51.672
reason is not that they were
mad or they wanted to make life

00:27:51.752 --> 00:27:59.092
hell, but because the syllables derive
from the writing of Sumerian words.

00:27:59.132 --> 00:28:02.912
So the Sumerian vocabulary
had a lot of words that were

00:28:02.952 --> 00:28:07.132
probably differentiated by tone.

00:28:07.152 --> 00:28:11.022
So you might have "Ba" and then a
rising "A" and then a lowering...

00:28:11.132 --> 00:28:14.932
And these signs all retain
the "Ba" value even though

00:28:14.992 --> 00:28:18.772
there were no tones. So it means if
you look at a sign list, there's a

00:28:18.851 --> 00:28:22.581
lot of signs. You have "Ba" number one, which
is the common. Then there's "Ba" number

00:28:22.652 --> 00:28:26.492
two, "Ba" number three, and you have to learn
them all. And when you read, you have to learn

00:28:26.552 --> 00:28:30.412
how to do it. So, in the
modern world, if you go to

00:28:30.452 --> 00:28:34.110
university to do Assyriology,
which I hope you and all of your

00:28:34.121 --> 00:28:37.962
disciples will do as soon as possible,
you actually have to cope with

00:28:38.032 --> 00:28:41.952
two languages: the Sumerian
and the Babylonian. Now, the

00:28:41.992 --> 00:28:44.851
first thing is this, that
the Babylonian language

00:28:45.792 --> 00:28:49.392
is a Semitic tongue, which
although it's extinct,

00:28:50.392 --> 00:28:54.112
is connected to or related
to Hebrew, Aramaic,

00:28:54.132 --> 00:28:58.112
Arabic, Ethiopic, Syriac.
All that family of Semitic

00:28:58.192 --> 00:29:01.452
languages which are still
alive. It's an early

00:29:01.512 --> 00:29:05.232
example of one of those. So
that when the decipherment came

00:29:05.292 --> 00:29:09.212
along, it was the Semitic
dictionary that they fell back

00:29:09.272 --> 00:29:12.072
on to identify words, nouns, and

00:29:12.112 --> 00:29:16.012
roots. The other language, which
is Sumerian, the one when you

00:29:16.092 --> 00:29:20.042
stick bits in the beginning and
stick bits at the end, is not only

00:29:20.112 --> 00:29:24.952
not Semitic, it's not related
to any other known language.

00:29:25.312 --> 00:29:26.331
- Oh, no.

00:29:26.351 --> 00:29:30.272
- Yeah, this is a bewitching thing. It's
a bewitching thing to me, and this

00:29:30.312 --> 00:29:34.172
is how to understand it.
Because the languages that we

00:29:34.252 --> 00:29:38.232
study in the world today,
linguists study, they more or less

00:29:38.812 --> 00:29:42.052
all fall into a language
group. So you have

00:29:42.092 --> 00:29:45.112
Indo-European with
Spanish, Italian, Latin,

00:29:45.132 --> 00:29:49.072
Hittite, and so forth, French, that's one

00:29:49.112 --> 00:29:52.592
group. And you have Germanic
and you have Slavonic. And most

00:29:52.632 --> 00:29:56.392
languages, even the far-flung ones,
fall into what can be seen to be

00:29:56.492 --> 00:30:00.392
maybe big and airy groups,
their family like that. There's

00:30:00.492 --> 00:30:04.331
not one for Sumerian.
So this means that the

00:30:04.432 --> 00:30:08.331
truth that languages do not exist
in a vacuum, but they're part of a

00:30:08.372 --> 00:30:12.292
big family, must always
have been true. So that

00:30:12.331 --> 00:30:19.131
when writing arrives about 3000,
say, 300 BC, to write properly.

00:30:19.192 --> 00:30:27.411
It means that Sumerian was recorded
just in time, but the big languages,

00:30:27.452 --> 00:30:33.671
maybe in China, in Russia, in somewhere else
in Asia, that were related to Sumerian,

00:30:33.712 --> 00:30:34.272
- Are gone?

00:30:34.292 --> 00:30:38.072
- ...are all gone. They're gone forever and
ever and ever, unless something amazing

00:30:38.091 --> 00:30:44.052
happens. So we've got the one representative
of this bizarre family. Is that-

00:30:44.091 --> 00:30:44.692
- Amazing.

00:30:44.752 --> 00:30:48.391
- It is. And it's a very
stimulating thing to imagine. I

00:30:48.452 --> 00:30:53.911
personally believe that Neanderthals
and early Homo sapiens, for sure,

00:30:55.012 --> 00:30:58.252
had language. For sure they talked to
one another. It's impossible that they

00:30:58.292 --> 00:31:02.052
didn't. The point came when
they did, they did. And

00:31:02.351 --> 00:31:06.212
the Neanderthals, 800,000
years of rural life

00:31:06.252 --> 00:31:09.952
in Europe, they had to deal with the Ice Age,
they all lived together, they bring up their

00:31:09.992 --> 00:31:13.861
children. You think they couldn't speak
anything? They have the same apparatus.

00:31:13.861 --> 00:31:17.841
And if you have a human brain,
then it responds to stimulus. And

00:31:17.871 --> 00:31:21.752
the more stimulus there is for
communication, I mean, the idea that you and

00:31:21.831 --> 00:31:27.851
I are out hunting rhino- ...and,
and, and you say, "Legs." Well, shut

00:31:27.911 --> 00:31:31.591
up, I'm concentrating. "Legs,
legs." And then I suddenly think,

00:31:31.611 --> 00:31:35.572
"Oh, I get it. You are Legs."

00:31:35.611 --> 00:31:39.522
Right? You only have to do that once, then
you know who I am. So I know that I'm

00:31:39.572 --> 00:31:42.742
me and that you are you. So
people who say that they couldn't

00:31:42.752 --> 00:31:46.572
distinguish ego and all that,
it's absolutely stupid. If you

00:31:46.611 --> 00:31:53.172
cut your hand with a knife, you sure as
hell experience... You sure as hell do. It

00:31:53.212 --> 00:31:54.232
hurts.

00:31:54.292 --> 00:31:57.772
hurts a lot. You might even bleed to
death. But it's not somebody else's hand,

00:31:59.091 --> 00:32:02.851
and it's your hand and it's your existence and
your life that's threatened. You think people

00:32:02.972 --> 00:32:06.792
weren't conscious that they were
an entity? I don't believe it.

00:32:06.871 --> 00:32:10.792
- And they probably had a way
to express that with sounds.

00:32:10.831 --> 00:32:13.371
- Well, eventually, yes. Names. I mean-

00:32:13.411 --> 00:32:13.772
- Names

00:32:13.891 --> 00:32:17.431
- ...names the things, and then
you have the idea that a label

00:32:17.591 --> 00:32:21.192
fixes to something. Then the light bulb
has gone on, and next minute you have

00:32:21.312 --> 00:32:25.212
rhino, and you have skin, and you
have babies, and you... Because

00:32:25.311 --> 00:32:29.302
I think you have an idea, and the idea then
drives the brain, and the brain has another

00:32:29.331 --> 00:32:31.581
idea. It works like fertility.

00:32:31.611 --> 00:32:35.091
- So what do you think is the motivation,
the primary driver of developing written

00:32:35.192 --> 00:32:40.012
language? Is it... Does it go
hand-in-hand with civilization?

00:32:40.131 --> 00:32:44.111
- I think that the media in which it
appears is when there's a lot of

00:32:44.172 --> 00:32:47.371
people living in an urban environment.

00:32:47.562 --> 00:32:51.431
And with rival institutions
or the king or the government

00:32:51.492 --> 00:32:54.002
or all those sorts of things.

00:32:54.002 --> 00:32:57.931
And that's why I think Gobekle
Tepe must have been the

00:32:57.992 --> 00:33:01.812
same thing. I read somewhere that
they're all nomads and they only came to

00:33:01.851 --> 00:33:05.032
Gobekle Tepe, you know, three
months a year. I mean, that

00:33:05.151 --> 00:33:08.742
cannot be true that they
were nomads, and they...

00:33:08.952 --> 00:33:12.752
Cannot be true. To get
the stone and someone has

00:33:12.792 --> 00:33:16.772
to draw on the ground the plan of the
building, they have to work out how thick

00:33:16.831 --> 00:33:20.841
it's going to be, how high it's going to
be. I mean, you can't just, you know,

00:33:22.111 --> 00:33:24.992
like that, like gorillas.

00:33:25.151 --> 00:33:28.651
- All right. So, deciphering,
the process of deciphering.

00:33:28.871 --> 00:33:32.371
- So when I started, there were
grammars and scientists, and

00:33:32.431 --> 00:33:36.212
dictionaries. Everything was marvelous. It was all
basically deciphered. All you had to do was get on with

00:33:36.272 --> 00:33:39.212
learning it. But at the
beginning, when the first

00:33:39.292 --> 00:33:42.891
tablets and bricks in cuneiform and stone

00:33:42.952 --> 00:33:46.722
inscriptions came to light, no one could
read them. But they knew they were

00:33:46.772 --> 00:33:50.472
writing, but they didn't know how to read
them. And what happened was, like you said

00:33:50.532 --> 00:33:54.012
before, with the Rosetta Stone,
it was something directly

00:33:54.091 --> 00:33:58.032
comparable, because there
was an inscription of

00:33:58.091 --> 00:34:01.931
one of the Persian kings halfway
up a mountain in a place

00:34:01.992 --> 00:34:08.761
called Bisutun, where this King Darius
had written an account of his successful

00:34:08.891 --> 00:34:15.721
career in Elamite and in
Babylonian and in Old Persian,

00:34:16.331 --> 00:34:20.072
a trilingual version. And
Old Persian, although

00:34:20.092 --> 00:34:23.692
it's obviously an archaic form of
the language, Persian is still

00:34:23.752 --> 00:34:27.491
alive. It was still alive in the
19th century. So, since the Old

00:34:27.572 --> 00:34:31.562
Persian was written in a very simple
style of cuneiform, they deciphered it,

00:34:31.612 --> 00:34:35.431
they twigged it was Old Persian,
they read it in Persian, and they

00:34:35.471 --> 00:34:38.991
read the names Daray awush
in Old Persian. And then

00:34:39.112 --> 00:34:43.402
suddenly, somebody realized that the other
two columns were about the same length.

00:34:43.911 --> 00:34:44.172
- Brilliant.

00:34:44.232 --> 00:34:48.212
- What do you know? And the thing is, it said,
"I am Darius the great king, king of the

00:34:48.272 --> 00:34:52.232
world, king of the... son of... grandson of..."
So there's a whole paragraph with repeated things

00:34:52.272 --> 00:35:00.062
in the Persian which they could understand.
So what do you know? They're reiterated

00:35:00.112 --> 00:35:04.092
passages in the other two
languages. So that was the key,

00:35:04.132 --> 00:35:07.732
that kind of... the chisel that opened up

00:35:07.792 --> 00:35:11.232
cuneiform writing proper.
And the thing was, they soon

00:35:11.312 --> 00:35:15.282
twigged that the language of
the Babylonian was a Semitic

00:35:15.412 --> 00:35:19.241
tongue. And this was so important. I
think the first word they discovered

00:35:19.772 --> 00:35:27.532
was the word for river, which is Naharu in
Akkadian and نحر in Arabic and Aramaic.

00:35:27.892 --> 00:35:31.872
And when they realized that the word
that corresponded to the Persian

00:35:31.892 --> 00:35:35.372
had this form, this was a gift, a gift of

00:35:35.392 --> 00:35:38.971
gold, because everybody immediately
seized their Arabic and Hebrew

00:35:39.032 --> 00:35:42.971
dictionaries and started leafing through,
looking for words that would fit in the context.

00:35:42.991 --> 00:35:46.692
And they basically deciphered
this inscription in that

00:35:46.792 --> 00:35:50.412
sort of way. And of course, all
the other inscriptions came in

00:35:50.532 --> 00:35:54.252
order, and there were lots and lots of
difficulties which had to be resolved, but

00:35:54.312 --> 00:35:57.471
that's the basic thing. And
without that trilingual,

00:35:58.452 --> 00:36:02.142
I don't know what would have
happened. I mean, I suppose it's

00:36:02.172 --> 00:36:06.002
conceivable that in the very
modern world, something

00:36:06.011 --> 00:36:09.352
might have happened. But as
it was, it was done by sheer

00:36:09.412 --> 00:36:13.392
brainpower, by very, very
clever persons just doing

00:36:13.452 --> 00:36:17.310
it. And they cracked it. The Elamite
language is much more difficult, but they...

00:36:17.319 --> 00:36:21.160
got a lot of it too. So, it was a
very romantic thing because the

00:36:21.200 --> 00:36:25.049
inscription was carved on a mountain
face far above the plain, and

00:36:25.100 --> 00:36:28.899
Henry Rawlinson, who was an
upstanding young British

00:36:28.960 --> 00:36:32.899
officer who claimed to decipher
cuneiform quite unjustifiably,

00:36:32.960 --> 00:36:36.240
climbed up there with some
miserable kid and made

00:36:36.819 --> 00:36:40.779
squeezes of the whole thing overlooking
the plain, thousands of feet up in the

00:36:40.839 --> 00:36:44.620
air, and brought those back, and they
were used in the decipherment. So,

00:36:45.040 --> 00:36:46.200
it's very romantic.

00:36:46.240 --> 00:36:50.160
- Wait a minute. A more controversial
statement from today. Henry

00:36:50.200 --> 00:36:52.600
Rawlinson doesn't deserve
the credit for that?

00:36:52.620 --> 00:36:56.490
- No, I don't think he does. He's called
the Father of Assyriology, but I

00:36:56.560 --> 00:37:00.180
think he's the Stepfather of Assyriology
because when he first got these

00:37:00.220 --> 00:37:05.180
inscriptions, he wrote a long book about
it, which was almost entirely wrong.

00:37:05.220 --> 00:37:09.100
And there was a clergyman in Northern
Ireland called Edward Hincks

00:37:10.259 --> 00:37:13.660
who lived in a place called Killyleagh
and had five daughters and ran this

00:37:13.720 --> 00:37:20.460
church, who was possibly a card-carrying
genius, if not jolly, jolly

00:37:20.520 --> 00:37:24.420
close. And what happened
with him was this. There was

00:37:24.480 --> 00:37:28.020
an ongoing competition...
well, an ongoing challenge to

00:37:28.040 --> 00:37:31.399
decipher hieroglyphic writing, which
Champollion usually gets the credit

00:37:31.460 --> 00:37:35.220
for, and Hincks was very
interested in trying to

00:37:35.240 --> 00:37:39.080
decipher hieroglyphic ahead of the French.

00:37:39.140 --> 00:37:42.850
And he ran into a sort of dead end at one
stage, and he thought he'd have a look at

00:37:42.899 --> 00:37:50.680
cuneiform to see if it was helpful.
And at the same time, he cracked it.

00:37:50.720 --> 00:37:54.700
He worked out how it worked. He realized
that one sign can have more than one value

00:37:55.060 --> 00:37:59.020
of sound and of meaning because they
are multivalent, the signs. I tried to

00:37:59.040 --> 00:38:04.440
shelter you from the horrible news. But
it actually, it's not a walk in the

00:38:04.540 --> 00:38:11.879
park. It takes about five years to you
probably do it in about four, probably.

00:38:11.940 --> 00:38:15.920
- That is a compliment. I think
you just complimented me. Thank

00:38:15.980 --> 00:38:17.540
you. Thank you very much.

00:38:19.379 --> 00:38:23.100
So, you're saying one sign that looks
exactly the same might have different

00:38:23.200 --> 00:38:24.879
sounds, given the context?

00:38:24.940 --> 00:38:28.868
- Yeah, and you have to
choose the right sound, and

00:38:28.899 --> 00:38:32.709
also different meaning as well.
Because for example, if you have a

00:38:32.740 --> 00:38:36.359
sign for "hot," the word "hot,"
right? You can't really have a

00:38:36.399 --> 00:38:37.819
picture sign for "hot."

00:38:39.160 --> 00:38:43.879
It doesn't make sense, but what they
did is they did a drawing of a kind of

00:38:45.080 --> 00:38:48.720
complex thing with a brazier inside
another sign which meant "hot."

00:38:49.100 --> 00:38:52.980
So that sign existed, but it also meant
other things as well, and you had to choose

00:38:53.020 --> 00:38:56.920
the right one for the context. All the
context do matter. I mean, it really

00:38:56.929 --> 00:39:00.799
is quite a matter for despair
when you start cuneiform, because

00:39:00.859 --> 00:39:04.520
on top of everything else, they
didn't leave gaps between the words.

00:39:04.540 --> 00:39:04.750
And that's really...

00:39:04.750 --> 00:39:05.440
- So they're all connected?

00:39:05.480 --> 00:39:11.140
- That's really mean. Yeah. So when you read
what you have to do, you start with the

00:39:11.180 --> 00:39:14.980
first sign, and you think of
the sign, and you go through

00:39:15.020 --> 00:39:18.129
the values in your mind,
and there's the next sign.

00:39:18.140 --> 00:39:22.060
And if one is "ba" and the next
one is "ab" among other readings,

00:39:22.100 --> 00:39:26.500
"ba-ab" sounds like a syllable structure
for a word, and you go on like that.

00:39:26.560 --> 00:39:30.359
So there are two things about it. One
is that if you want to, you can master

00:39:30.480 --> 00:39:33.799
it. The other thing is that
the number of variables was

00:39:33.839 --> 00:39:37.680
restricted. They controlled
it, so it wasn't insane.

00:39:37.720 --> 00:39:41.540
So in other words, if you learn the corpus and you
would learn how the signs are composed and you

00:39:41.600 --> 00:39:46.910
learn their different values, then you've
got it down. ...And off you go. And

00:39:48.220 --> 00:39:51.379
it's very beautiful, I
think. It's marvelous.

00:39:51.440 --> 00:39:55.339
- Can you, in all seriousness, take me back
to the time when you were learning it?

00:39:55.460 --> 00:39:55.470
- Yes.

00:39:55.480 --> 00:39:57.279
- What's the process of learning it?

00:39:57.339 --> 00:40:01.279
- Well, I had a very abnormal upbringing
because when I went to university,

00:40:01.779 --> 00:40:06.759
for about three years beforehand
I'd wanted to be an Egyptologist.

00:40:06.799 --> 00:40:13.040
So I read the grammar by Gardiner and
was looking forward very much to study

00:40:13.049 --> 00:40:16.609
ancient Egyptian, and what
happened was that I went up to the

00:40:16.640 --> 00:40:20.799
University of Birmingham where
I went to university, and

00:40:22.040 --> 00:40:26.020
there was a man called Rundle Clark,
who was an Egyptologist, and Rundle

00:40:26.100 --> 00:40:29.520
Clark came in on the Monday
and gave us one lesson about

00:40:29.779 --> 00:40:34.939
Egyptian sculpture or something like
that, and the next day he died.

00:40:36.100 --> 00:40:42.859
Bang. So, the professor called
me into his room and said,

00:40:42.870 --> 00:40:46.839
"Look, it's going to take me a while
to get an Egyptologist. They don't

00:40:46.880 --> 00:40:50.560
grow on trees, but there's another
person in this department who

00:40:50.600 --> 00:40:53.939
teaches another ancient language,
called Lambert, and he teaches

00:40:53.980 --> 00:40:57.720
cuneiform. So what I suggest
is you go and do a bit of

00:40:57.740 --> 00:41:01.540
cuneiform with Professor Lambert, and
then when I get an Egyptologist, you can

00:41:01.580 --> 00:41:09.460
convert back." So I go and knock on
the door. "Yes?" I went in and said,

00:41:09.520 --> 00:41:13.500
"I want to learn cuneiform."
And Professor Lambert, who was

00:41:14.000 --> 00:41:19.939
rather a Sherlock Holmes kind of figure,
aesthetic, bony, sarcastic, cruel.

00:41:20.000 --> 00:41:20.720
- Cruel.

00:41:20.740 --> 00:41:24.339
- Cruel, absolutely terrifying, and I said

00:41:24.580 --> 00:41:28.500
I wanted to learn cuneiform,
and he wasn't at all pleased

00:41:28.540 --> 00:41:33.250
because this was a time in
Britain when professors

00:41:34.680 --> 00:41:38.920
resented having students to teach because
it butted into their research time.

00:41:39.000 --> 00:41:40.270
It was that sort of arrangement.

00:41:40.359 --> 00:41:40.549
- Yes.

00:41:40.600 --> 00:41:44.330
- Anyway, I started it off and
after about, I don't know,

00:41:44.380 --> 00:41:48.180
maybe one or maybe two lessons, I knew
this was going to be my life's work. So

00:41:48.220 --> 00:41:52.080
that's what happened to me. It was
an amazing thing. So he gave me a

00:41:52.120 --> 00:41:56.040
list of signs to learn, basic signs.

00:41:56.120 --> 00:42:02.180
So I did, in the next couple of days, and
then we came in and we started reading.

00:42:02.240 --> 00:42:10.040
- So, given the complexity of the signs,
why did cuneiform last 3,000 years?

00:42:10.120 --> 00:42:12.420
The most successful writing system ever.

00:42:12.480 --> 00:42:19.572
- Fair question. There are several factors.
One is the famous factor of inertia.

00:42:19.632 --> 00:42:23.402
The second thing is that
people who could read and

00:42:23.452 --> 00:42:27.372
write, and were in charge
of archives, and were the

00:42:27.472 --> 00:42:31.082
clerks in the temple,
and the writers for the

00:42:31.192 --> 00:42:35.172
king and everything, commanded
a very great deal of power

00:42:35.692 --> 00:42:39.532
because most of the public couldn't.

00:42:39.602 --> 00:42:43.432
So they reserved to themselves
knowledge, understanding,

00:42:44.172 --> 00:42:47.772
philosophical inquiry. I mean,
no doubt it went on in pubs and

00:42:47.812 --> 00:42:51.141
things, but they were in charge.
They had everything under lock and

00:42:51.272 --> 00:42:55.072
key. And I think the
scribal schools are rather

00:42:55.132 --> 00:42:58.952
cliquey. They were
certainly cliquey in the

00:42:59.012 --> 00:43:02.152
sense of Oxford and Cambridge
being rivals, that sort of thing.

00:43:02.162 --> 00:43:06.072
They had that sort of idea, and
it was in no one's interest

00:43:06.112 --> 00:43:09.901
whatsoever. Nobody would ever
concede any interest in the

00:43:09.972 --> 00:43:16.512
idea of literacy for all. This would
never be thought of, and it would be

00:43:16.552 --> 00:43:20.512
anathema. And so if you got on a soapbox
on a Saturday afternoon and said,

00:43:20.532 --> 00:43:25.712
"Oh, enough of this, we have to teach the
children," they'd be taken away, I think.

00:43:25.792 --> 00:43:29.312
- So we're getting, in these
tablets, the output of the

00:43:29.332 --> 00:43:33.372
intellectual class, a very
small fraction of humans.

00:43:33.392 --> 00:43:35.872
So we're getting just the
Oxford and the Cambridge.

00:43:35.912 --> 00:43:39.592
- We are, except that when you went
to scribal school, you had to

00:43:39.612 --> 00:43:43.212
learn Sumerian and Akkadian, the
languages properly, and all the

00:43:43.292 --> 00:43:45.712
vocabulary and the grammar.

00:43:45.872 --> 00:43:53.192
So some boys probably had a lot of
trouble doing this. And, you know,

00:43:54.372 --> 00:43:57.832
they were okay, but then there ain't
gonna be no geniuses. And I think the

00:43:57.872 --> 00:44:01.292
situation in the school was
that the teachers farmed out

00:44:01.872 --> 00:44:05.772
the kids who would actually rather have
been outside playing football but could

00:44:05.792 --> 00:44:09.372
read and write, to earning
their living doing

00:44:09.592 --> 00:44:12.732
low-level reading and writing.
That's to say, writing

00:44:12.872 --> 00:44:16.292
contracts, letters, everyday things for

00:44:16.332 --> 00:44:19.812
people. Because no one could read
and write, so you had to get a

00:44:19.972 --> 00:44:23.882
scribe if you're gonna marry your daughter
off, and you get all the witnesses about

00:44:23.932 --> 00:44:27.852
the presence and all this, all that
thing had to be done for four days. So

00:44:27.952 --> 00:44:31.292
the writer would come and do... So your

00:44:31.852 --> 00:44:35.772
medium-level writers would
serve that requirement. And

00:44:35.852 --> 00:44:39.752
very talented or clever
or intellectual students

00:44:40.292 --> 00:44:44.232
would be encouraged to go into
one of the literary professions,

00:44:44.272 --> 00:44:50.422
which would be, so to speak,
medicine, law, working for the

00:44:50.492 --> 00:44:54.032
king, working for the Church,
I mean, the priesthood, so

00:44:54.412 --> 00:44:58.001
all those things which were dependent upon
archives and writing, they would find their

00:44:58.072 --> 00:45:02.032
niveau. And also architecture, because

00:45:02.092 --> 00:45:05.832
if a big building had to be built,
then somebody had to know about load

00:45:05.932 --> 00:45:09.912
bearing things and brick measurements.
And so some of them went into

00:45:09.952 --> 00:45:13.912
that kind of work. And also, probably
some of them went into running

00:45:13.952 --> 00:45:17.912
the army and you had to move
stores and animals. So they,

00:45:17.932 --> 00:45:21.652
they found their niveau, and
some of them were intellectually

00:45:21.712 --> 00:45:25.682
very able indeed, and they went into,

00:45:25.752 --> 00:45:31.332
the disciplines of, on the one hand,
astrology, but more seriously into astronomy

00:45:32.332 --> 00:45:35.832
and theoretical grammar,
because they had treatises

00:45:35.932 --> 00:45:39.812
about the relationship between the
two languages and how they worked and

00:45:40.172 --> 00:45:43.612
different parts of speech, and
they wrote learned commentaries as

00:45:43.652 --> 00:45:46.792
well, what words meant. So
there was an intellectual

00:45:47.912 --> 00:45:51.832
high-level top, and then there were
lots of professional scribes, and then

00:45:51.872 --> 00:45:57.472
the kids who left school as soon as
possible and did all that, like today.

00:45:57.512 --> 00:46:00.852
- I apologize to be philosophical,
but Wittgenstein, the

00:46:00.872 --> 00:46:04.792
philosopher, said, "The limits of
our language is the limits of our

00:46:04.892 --> 00:46:11.612
world." So to what degree did the languages
that were encoded in cuneiform define

00:46:12.112 --> 00:46:16.012
human civilization, would you say?
What were the things that were

00:46:16.052 --> 00:46:21.652
complicated to express and
therefore were not expressed often?

00:46:21.712 --> 00:46:28.912
- That's a really interesting question.
So in terms of richness of vocabulary

00:46:30.012 --> 00:46:37.312
and richness of verbal subtlety, I think
Babylonian rivals Arabic and of course

00:46:37.372 --> 00:46:41.752
English. In other words, you can
say whatever you want in English,

00:46:41.762 --> 00:46:45.652
however subtle it might be, even if
people understand the subtlety. You can

00:46:45.672 --> 00:46:49.632
because the tools are fantastic. And
Arabic has lots of synonyms and lots

00:46:49.712 --> 00:46:53.202
of devices and all the same.
Same in Babylonian. It was a

00:46:53.252 --> 00:46:56.962
fully-fledged literary language. The

00:46:56.992 --> 00:47:00.772
question about whether the
language put a stop to

00:47:00.892 --> 00:47:04.542
further things, which is
basically what you're asking,

00:47:05.372 --> 00:47:11.152
is immensely complicated. But the one
thing that strikes me as relevant

00:47:12.192 --> 00:47:15.112
is that a very huge proportion of

00:47:16.212 --> 00:47:19.892
scholarly literature in
Mesopotamia, it takes the form of

00:47:19.952 --> 00:47:23.792
omens, because they believed that events,

00:47:23.912 --> 00:47:27.802
accidental or deliberately
stimulated, had implications for

00:47:27.832 --> 00:47:29.482
what was going to happen.

00:47:29.512 --> 00:47:33.312
And they took omens from things
in the sky and things in the

00:47:33.492 --> 00:47:37.172
street and every single
thing. If you were a

00:47:37.732 --> 00:47:43.322
well-qualified diviner, it would
have this significance. Right? Now,

00:47:44.272 --> 00:47:48.212
there are thousands of
lines of omens, of all

00:47:48.252 --> 00:47:52.072
different kinds. And in
Akkadian, it says, for

00:47:52.132 --> 00:47:55.882
example, "If a lizard runs
across the breakfast table, the

00:47:55.952 --> 00:47:59.912
queen will die." So if you
translate the Akkadian this way,

00:47:59.932 --> 00:48:02.792
the word, "if," verb, and
everything, "If that, then

00:48:02.872 --> 00:48:06.812
this." So there are
thousands of, thousands of

00:48:06.892 --> 00:48:10.342
lines translated into many books about
omens where, "If this happens, that will

00:48:10.432 --> 00:48:14.872
happen." So this is how it's
understood by my colleagues.

00:48:15.932 --> 00:48:19.892
Well, this is absolutely impossible
because if you are the chief diviner

00:48:19.932 --> 00:48:23.872
for the king and you open up a

00:48:23.912 --> 00:48:27.611
sheep to take a liver out and
examine it according to the... And

00:48:27.912 --> 00:48:31.812
if the queen's going to die and the king's
there, you're not going to say, "The queen's

00:48:31.832 --> 00:48:36.192
going to die." I mean, you're going to look
like a fucking idiot if she doesn't die.

00:48:36.212 --> 00:48:40.052
And if she does die, you're going to
be responsible. So all you can ever

00:48:40.112 --> 00:48:43.772
do and ever, ever have been able
to do is to say, "There's a

00:48:43.852 --> 00:48:47.672
sign here that says that the
queen could die." Meaning,

00:48:47.992 --> 00:48:51.752
could die, not will die. And
therefore, the requisite

00:48:51.932 --> 00:48:55.232
ritual or magic must immediately
swing into action to

00:48:55.272 --> 00:49:02.812
defer the danger. So the point is
that A equals B is never true.

00:49:02.892 --> 00:49:10.432
It means that with A, B could be, might
be, ought to be, should be, could be

00:49:10.472 --> 00:49:14.352
true, all those subtle things.
So that the diviner who works

00:49:14.372 --> 00:49:18.072
for the king must have been a philosopher

00:49:18.452 --> 00:49:21.852
who looks at the king, he
looks at the king and he

00:49:22.012 --> 00:49:26.032
knows what the king wants him to
say. So he has to tell the king

00:49:27.332 --> 00:49:31.112
what he wants to hear. He has to tell the
king if it's bad news in such a way that he

00:49:31.132 --> 00:49:36.092
doesn't mind it or he won't worry. It's
the most beautiful thing. It's so subtle.

00:49:36.112 --> 00:49:43.352
It's, it's like a violin concerto. It
can never have been A equals B for a

00:49:43.432 --> 00:49:47.222
minute. So the medical texts
say, "If a man has this,"

00:49:47.252 --> 00:49:50.702
doo-dee-dee-doo, you know? "You do this,
your drink's..." He'll get better. Right?

00:49:50.772 --> 00:49:53.532
He says, "You'll get better."
Have you ever met a doctor

00:49:54.552 --> 00:49:58.392
who will say, "You do this, you'll
get better"? No. They say, "All

00:49:58.432 --> 00:50:02.352
being well, you'll be back on your feet."
Or, "I've seen this kind of condition many

00:50:02.372 --> 00:50:06.272
times, everything should go fine. You should
get better, you should be better soon." But

00:50:06.392 --> 00:50:10.492
never, "You will get better," because
what happens if you die? Where are you?

00:50:10.612 --> 00:50:12.152
- The lawyers will show up.

00:50:12.172 --> 00:50:18.972
- Absolutely. So this means that not
expressible in Akkadian grammar are these

00:50:19.052 --> 00:50:24.352
modal verbs. ...Could, might, should,
ought. They can't be expressed

00:50:24.412 --> 00:50:28.332
grammatically, but it is
impossible that it was such

00:50:28.492 --> 00:50:31.972
a magnificent literary
language, where they

00:50:33.072 --> 00:50:36.952
didn't have these subtleties.
It's utterly impossible. And

00:50:37.032 --> 00:50:40.852
if you translate, "He will," in a literary

00:50:40.931 --> 00:50:45.221
text, "He might," then the whole text is
different. The whole text is different.

00:50:45.252 --> 00:50:46.232
- Yeah, absolutely.

00:50:46.242 --> 00:50:49.672
- And they don't... My colleagues
translate... It says in the grammar books,

00:50:49.992 --> 00:50:57.132
like that, automatically. There's no
self-appraisal of the folly of it.

00:50:57.232 --> 00:51:00.812
- You have said the translation is part
archeology, part detective work, part

00:51:00.892 --> 00:51:05.232
poetry. Can we just speak about
translation and the art of it a bit more?

00:51:05.292 --> 00:51:06.192
- Yes.

00:51:06.232 --> 00:51:10.142
- I mean, it's such an
incredible discipline.

00:51:10.172 --> 00:51:14.112
Just like you said, hinted
at, just a subtle variation

00:51:14.152 --> 00:51:16.852
in a single word can change everything.

00:51:16.892 --> 00:51:20.752
- Well, you know, the truth
about translation is that

00:51:20.772 --> 00:51:26.872
you never really have a word in one
language which precisely equates another.

00:51:26.932 --> 00:51:30.712
You never do. They're always a kind of the

00:51:30.732 --> 00:51:34.112
best you can do. And sometimes it makes no
difference and sometimes it's really quite

00:51:34.152 --> 00:51:35.532
misleading. And so

00:51:36.972 --> 00:51:40.932
what people do when they learn Akkadian, is
they learn the Akkadian word and they learn the

00:51:40.972 --> 00:51:44.902
English translation, right?
You have, "To divide."

00:51:44.952 --> 00:51:48.322
So whenever you have the verb,
it's some form of divide or

00:51:48.392 --> 00:51:52.162
division. But actually it's
not, because divide is like the

00:51:52.192 --> 00:51:54.992
primary root, but there's maybe 10

00:51:55.012 --> 00:51:58.941
nuances of what that can mean
in English, where the one at

00:51:58.972 --> 00:52:02.752
the bottom and the one at the top, you'd hardly
know they were connected. And the Chicago

00:52:02.852 --> 00:52:06.732
Dictionary, which is such a magnificent
thing, when you come to the museum and

00:52:06.792 --> 00:52:11.752
see me, I'll show you this. It's
the most salient and important

00:52:11.812 --> 00:52:15.512
thing that came out of America in
all its history, is the Chicago

00:52:15.552 --> 00:52:18.992
Assyrian Dictionary, which is
this long. There's only one

00:52:19.132 --> 00:52:22.892
rival to it for cultural importance,
which is the electric guitar, of

00:52:22.952 --> 00:52:28.412
course. But the two of them, I think, are
your countrymen's greatest achievement.

00:52:29.512 --> 00:52:31.032
- It's the pride of our nation.

00:52:31.112 --> 00:52:31.472
- I think so.

00:52:31.482 --> 00:52:32.172
- ...those two things.

00:52:32.212 --> 00:52:33.632
- The very thing.

00:52:33.672 --> 00:52:37.652
- Chicago dictionary. Can you... I'm sorry to take
the attention. What is the Chicago Dictionary?

00:52:37.712 --> 00:52:42.252
- It started in the '20s, and they made a
dictionary of the Babylonian language.

00:52:42.312 --> 00:52:42.632
- Ah.

00:52:42.642 --> 00:52:46.572
- A to Z, so to speak. And it's as long
as this table. It's a magnificent

00:52:46.632 --> 00:52:50.552
thing, and this big. And
the people who worked on

00:52:50.592 --> 00:52:54.512
it were real translators, so they
knew that it wasn't lexically A

00:52:54.552 --> 00:52:57.312
means B, but they had... So
if you have something in a

00:52:57.352 --> 00:53:01.332
proverb, the meaning is gonna
be a little bit different

00:53:01.372 --> 00:53:05.082
from in their letter. And, you
know, so people really, really

00:53:05.172 --> 00:53:09.032
understand Akkadian, they really
do. But this thing about the modal

00:53:09.132 --> 00:53:11.912
verbs is an interesting
conundrum to me, because

00:53:12.792 --> 00:53:16.552
there's no way it's reflected
in the writing. So I can only

00:53:16.592 --> 00:53:20.422
assume that there was some
kind of drawing out of the

00:53:20.492 --> 00:53:24.331
vowel in a verb, meaning "could".
Like you were saying, it

00:53:24.432 --> 00:53:28.352
might do it, something like
that. Anyway, nowadays we— it's

00:53:28.362 --> 00:53:31.682
not the decipherment that's
the job; it's just reading.

00:53:31.682 --> 00:53:35.652
And if you have lots of tablets to
work on, like on a dig, it's very

00:53:35.692 --> 00:53:38.952
exciting if they come out of the ground and no
one's looked for them before you. It's your job.

00:53:39.012 --> 00:53:42.932
And if you're a competent Assyriologist,

00:53:43.012 --> 00:53:46.832
you should be able to
sight-read more or less.

00:53:46.872 --> 00:53:50.452
Except most— say, a letter or
something like that, but most

00:53:50.752 --> 00:53:54.672
documents have some damage, so you
have to learn how to interpret

00:53:55.272 --> 00:53:59.212
stuff. And also, some literature is
very difficult because of technical

00:53:59.272 --> 00:54:03.112
vocabulary, and then they had technical
vocabulary and unusual words.

00:54:03.172 --> 00:54:09.952
- So you can do all of that. You can kind
of figure out the technical complexities.

00:54:09.972 --> 00:54:14.232
You can figure out the noise,
meaning missing pieces.

00:54:14.632 --> 00:54:19.872
- Yeah. Sometimes you can calculate what it
ought to be, make a reasonable suggestion.

00:54:19.912 --> 00:54:23.822
And this dictionary, which I was talking
to you about, is such a fantastic

00:54:23.932 --> 00:54:27.744
tool, because a lot of people
worked on it. It was for

00:54:27.784 --> 00:54:31.464
the National Endowment for the
Humanities, and it was for

00:54:31.504 --> 00:54:34.804
decades and decades of work.
And most of the world's best

00:54:34.824 --> 00:54:38.804
Assyriologists collaborated on
it. So the quality of translation

00:54:38.844 --> 00:54:41.624
and understanding is really extraordinary.

00:54:41.664 --> 00:54:45.604
- What are some things you've read
from that time? Is there some

00:54:45.664 --> 00:54:48.024
jokes? Is there some love letters?

00:54:48.064 --> 00:54:51.564
- There are one or two letters
about that from a chap to a woman

00:54:51.604 --> 00:54:55.584
about, you know, "You are very beautiful
and your lips are like radishes and

00:54:55.624 --> 00:54:59.584
your ears are like walruses," and
things. But there are some things like

00:54:59.644 --> 00:55:03.433
that. And then there's a kind of
street drama in Babylon, in 4th

00:55:03.524 --> 00:55:07.124
century BC, something like
that, when there must have been

00:55:07.284 --> 00:55:14.084
actors who did this in the
street. And it's Marduk and

00:55:14.504 --> 00:55:21.064
Sarpanitum, his wife, and another woman.
Marduk's having an affair with this other—

00:55:21.084 --> 00:55:21.444
- Oh, no.

00:55:21.904 --> 00:55:25.014
- goddess. And Sarpanitum is
jealous, and these women

00:55:26.184 --> 00:55:30.064
fight in the street and hurl insults at one another,
and, you know, "slop bucket" and all this kind of

00:55:30.104 --> 00:55:33.744
stuff. It's hilarious, and it must
have been a bit like a, sort of

00:55:33.844 --> 00:55:37.204
Verdi opera without the music,
I suppose. I don't know. But

00:55:37.724 --> 00:55:39.874
anyway, it starts off when

00:55:41.044 --> 00:55:44.904
Sarpanitum is in the room and Marduk's
in bed with this other goddess

00:55:44.984 --> 00:55:50.184
on the roof and she can hear. You could
say it was an eternal human issue.

00:55:50.244 --> 00:55:53.564
- Yeah, yeah, love, heartbreak,
jealousy, all of that.

00:55:53.574 --> 00:55:55.344
- And between deities also.

00:55:55.364 --> 00:55:58.294
Because deities are only modeled
on human beings, after all, so...

00:55:58.304 --> 00:56:01.884
- Yeah, deities is a grandiose
way of expressing human

00:56:02.304 --> 00:56:06.784
affairs, human behaviors,
human ways, yeah.

00:56:06.804 --> 00:56:10.224
In the writing, what was their
relationship to the divine?

00:56:10.304 --> 00:56:13.444
- Relationship with the divine,
well, the first thing to

00:56:13.684 --> 00:56:19.884
say is that they had a large pantheon of
gods. So there were three gods at the

00:56:19.944 --> 00:56:23.864
top, sometimes called
Anu, Enlil, and Ea. There

00:56:23.884 --> 00:56:27.504
were three gods at the top and
hundreds of other gods and

00:56:27.604 --> 00:56:31.424
goddesses. And you have the situation

00:56:31.464 --> 00:56:34.584
that I think lots of small
villages and towns had their

00:56:35.503 --> 00:56:39.304
old, ancient gods, and eventually they
were all worked into a kind of theological

00:56:39.444 --> 00:56:43.204
system like a phone book. And the
lesser, minor gods were amalgamated

00:56:43.244 --> 00:56:47.164
and then they were given jobs in
the households of the big gods.

00:56:47.204 --> 00:56:49.624
So there was a sort of structure.

00:56:51.304 --> 00:56:55.284
So you have this in the background, a big, sweeping
theology, like you have in the world today in

00:56:55.344 --> 00:56:59.304
some parts of the world, and
this was the main system.

00:56:59.404 --> 00:57:02.814
And the main gods were concerned
with the ruler and the fate of the

00:57:02.884 --> 00:57:09.384
country, and another god was
concerned with illness and...

00:57:10.264 --> 00:57:14.204
and the dead and what happens to the
dead, and they had other specialties,

00:57:14.224 --> 00:57:18.224
and they all had their own temples.
And when a baby came into the world,

00:57:19.424 --> 00:57:23.404
probably this was universally
true, the baby was put

00:57:23.464 --> 00:57:27.144
under the tutelage of one
or other of the gods.

00:57:27.204 --> 00:57:30.684
Sometimes, you know, the royal family,
they were the big shots, but sometimes

00:57:31.104 --> 00:57:34.484
not, or the ones that were in the
family or something like that. So

00:57:34.984 --> 00:57:38.884
people had grown up with the
idea that among all of them,

00:57:38.964 --> 00:57:42.864
there were special ones for the
family and they had a special one who

00:57:42.884 --> 00:57:46.774
was supposed to look after them.
That's the sort of basic idea.

00:57:46.784 --> 00:57:50.724
But the trouble is, since gods
are, as you say, human beings on a

00:57:50.764 --> 00:57:54.714
larger scale, they can be
forgetful or uninterested

00:57:54.714 --> 00:57:58.664
or on holiday, and there are lots of
ways that you have to prompt your.

00:57:58.704 --> 00:58:02.144
Make little sacrifices and little
bribes so they do their job and keep an

00:58:02.204 --> 00:58:06.064
sacrifices and little bribes so
they do their job and keep an

00:58:06.124 --> 00:58:09.544
eye on you. So they had that kind
of slightly practical view of gods,

00:58:09.554 --> 00:58:12.674
that they were a bit unpredictable, "Great
when they were there but not always there"

00:58:12.724 --> 00:58:16.504
sort of idea. And I also believe this,
that a lot of people in the world today

00:58:16.624 --> 00:58:22.144
idea. And I also believe this, that
a lot of people in the world today

00:58:23.364 --> 00:58:27.084
who did not have the disadvantage
of growing up in a stifling

00:58:27.104 --> 00:58:30.924
religion, but are just normal
people, get a lot more interested

00:58:30.984 --> 00:58:34.584
when they're really ill or
when they have a big disaster.

00:58:35.084 --> 00:58:41.724
All of a sudden, God or gods seem
a lot more important than they do

00:58:41.823 --> 00:58:49.394
normally, so that few people walk about
in a state of religious awe, and a good

00:58:49.404 --> 00:58:53.104
proportion of clergymen I've ever
met don't do that either. It's a

00:58:53.184 --> 00:58:57.014
kind of conception that's not
actually based on reality, that

00:58:57.264 --> 00:59:00.224
the individual's response
to religious stimuli

00:59:01.184 --> 00:59:04.804
fluctuates and is varied and
is often a response to need.

00:59:05.344 --> 00:59:09.184
It doesn't come from nothing. I
mean, people don't suddenly feel,

00:59:09.224 --> 00:59:13.204
"I've got to thank the Lord for the
rainbow," or something like that.

00:59:13.264 --> 00:59:16.764
I think it's probably true
today. I mean, when you read

00:59:16.824 --> 00:59:20.204
the investigations they make of religion
today, Christianity in this country

00:59:20.284 --> 00:59:24.204
is on the decline, because people
who are supposed to be Christian

00:59:24.224 --> 00:59:28.204
say they aren't anymore, they're
atheists. And people who say,

00:59:28.224 --> 00:59:32.204
"I go to church and I believe in everything," it
is a relatively small number of people saying

00:59:32.224 --> 00:59:36.184
now this is the situation, which
is quite remarkable if you think

00:59:36.244 --> 00:59:40.064
about it. Lord knows what the consequence
will be for the human race, whether

00:59:40.104 --> 00:59:45.804
religion will balance out, whether
it will die off. Who knows?

00:59:45.864 --> 00:59:48.584
- I think it's an ancient
technology that has proven across

00:59:48.644 --> 00:59:56.524
millennia to give a set of tools to humans
to contend, as you said, with suffering.

00:59:56.544 --> 00:59:59.674
That's a part of life. So
when those rare moments come

01:00:00.644 --> 01:00:08.194
when you have to deal with deep pain, loss,
suffering, heartbreak, all those things...

01:00:08.194 --> 01:00:11.914
...looking up to the sky
and asking questions and

01:00:11.944 --> 01:00:15.314
trying to figure out the answers in
your conversation with the divine...

01:00:15.344 --> 01:00:18.214
- I think that's true, but I
think in Mesopotamia it was

01:00:18.244 --> 01:00:21.844
different in terms of its
potency and immediacy

01:00:22.244 --> 01:00:26.164
because there's no skyscrapers in
Iraq. You know, if you live in

01:00:26.204 --> 01:00:30.044
Southern Iraq and you sleep on
the roof, there are no lights at

01:00:30.124 --> 01:00:33.986
night. You're under the stars, you
can see everything 'cause of no smog

01:00:34.016 --> 01:00:37.976
and everything like that. And
the idea that the gods are there

01:00:38.256 --> 01:00:42.196
watching, it's not like
a big artifice like

01:00:42.236 --> 01:00:46.176
it is here. It just doesn't ring
true here. You can't come to it

01:00:46.776 --> 01:00:50.416
and really believe in it, whereas
these people didn't have to

01:00:50.476 --> 01:00:52.996
really believe in it because it was it.

01:00:53.036 --> 01:00:57.876
- It's the obvious practical part
of life. They're right there.

01:00:58.776 --> 01:01:02.656
- But it's not they didn't believe in
ghosts, they took them for granted.

01:01:02.676 --> 01:01:06.426
And they didn't believe in the gods, they
took them for granted. This is a different

01:01:06.476 --> 01:01:09.956
mechanism, because nobody here in the
world today takes those things for

01:01:09.976 --> 01:01:13.865
granted, just the opposite. But I think
that's how it worked. So you didn't

01:01:13.896 --> 01:01:17.886
have people wrestling with the
idea of whether the gods really

01:01:17.896 --> 01:01:21.436
exist or whether they really care about
me. They gave them a nudge when it was

01:01:21.476 --> 01:01:25.656
necessary, and they might offer
this, they might offer that, but it

01:01:26.576 --> 01:01:30.546
was the system, it was
the prevailing system.

01:01:30.556 --> 01:01:34.016
And I think it's an important
difference. And also that thing about

01:01:34.136 --> 01:01:38.056
ghosts is, that is clear from the
inscriptions, all of them that

01:01:38.136 --> 01:01:42.076
I managed to find, that
nobody ever asked themselves,

01:01:42.196 --> 01:01:46.136
"Do these things exist or
not?" Or, "Did I really see

01:01:46.176 --> 01:01:50.296
them or not?" They just took
it all for granted. Granted.

01:01:50.356 --> 01:01:53.936
- What are ghosts? Is it usually ancestors?

01:01:54.016 --> 01:01:57.856
- Well, everybody who died
in bed naturally or

01:01:57.976 --> 01:02:01.716
peacefully, what we call
their ghost, went down to the

01:02:01.776 --> 01:02:08.916
netherworld, and there they were. So they
buried people jolly quick for obvious

01:02:08.956 --> 01:02:12.686
reasons, and like they
do in Islam and Judaism

01:02:12.756 --> 01:02:18.356
today, it's the same kind of idea.
And the spirit of the person

01:02:19.576 --> 01:02:23.156
went down through the gates of
the netherworld and stayed there.

01:02:24.556 --> 01:02:27.736
So that's the basic situation.
And people in their houses had

01:02:28.596 --> 01:02:32.436
actual burials under the courtyard,
and they had a thing where you

01:02:32.556 --> 01:02:39.756
pour stuff down a hole, fluid and food,
kind of symbolic offerings to them.

01:02:39.816 --> 01:02:44.616
- So isn't that a way to lessen
the impact of mortality?

01:02:44.696 --> 01:02:48.586
- I don't know, because you
know that everyone's going

01:02:48.616 --> 01:02:52.376
to die. I think the real tragedy
would be if we're not supposed

01:02:52.446 --> 01:02:56.876
to. That would be the tragedy.
But every single person

01:02:58.296 --> 01:03:06.196
is going to die. So all relationships
have this finite clause in them. So if

01:03:06.256 --> 01:03:09.976
you're very fond of somebody or
you love somebody and they die,

01:03:10.056 --> 01:03:13.996
it's kind of infantile to whine about

01:03:14.066 --> 01:03:17.716
it ever after. Because what do you
think was going to happen? Either

01:03:17.836 --> 01:03:21.676
you or them. You know, I
always see it like that. I

01:03:21.756 --> 01:03:23.976
don't feel grief when people die.

01:03:24.096 --> 01:03:26.976
- It is infantile, but I've got to
tell you something about human

01:03:26.996 --> 01:03:30.426
beings. We're all kind of
infantile all the way through

01:03:30.456 --> 01:03:34.106
from, you know, we don't stop being
infantile after we're infants.

01:03:34.616 --> 01:03:36.856
It's- it's one thing to know it,

01:03:37.936 --> 01:03:41.876
you know, theoretically, and it's
another thing to know it know it. Like

01:03:41.936 --> 01:03:45.136
this thing ends, this ride ends.

01:03:45.156 --> 01:03:49.566
- But that's the pain, it's the
fact that the whole thing ends.

01:03:49.616 --> 01:03:53.956
And when people fall off the
edge, they fall off the edge.

01:03:54.016 --> 01:03:57.916
- So yeah, the knowledge that it ends is the
painful thing, not the actual moment of the

01:03:58.016 --> 01:04:02.456
ending. Many times what makes moments
really precious is that they're going to be

01:04:02.496 --> 01:04:06.316
gone. I think that's not a
trivial thing for us humans to

01:04:06.396 --> 01:04:10.096
really contend with. I
think religion, religious

01:04:10.136 --> 01:04:12.936
thought, the divine, I
think help with that.

01:04:12.996 --> 01:04:16.736
- I think the big mistake for
mankind was the creation of

01:04:16.776 --> 01:04:20.685
monotheistic religions, because
they brought evil into the

01:04:20.756 --> 01:04:24.596
world. Because if you believe in
a monotheistic religion, that

01:04:24.636 --> 01:04:30.956
means I'm right and you're wrong. If you
don't. So it's already on that footing.

01:04:31.036 --> 01:04:32.656
- It's very dogmatic. Yeah.

01:04:32.756 --> 01:04:36.636
- Dogmatic, and it's led to
everything. There are inquisitions

01:04:36.676 --> 01:04:40.596
and this, you know, all this kind of stuff.
It's all a result of it, that one religion is

01:04:40.606 --> 01:04:44.496
superior and the others should be stamped
out and all that. And in my opinion,

01:04:45.176 --> 01:04:48.796
monotheistic religion has
generated the most fantastic

01:04:48.856 --> 01:04:52.676
amount of non-religious
feeling. Whereas when you

01:04:52.736 --> 01:04:56.726
have all the different gods and they have
different specialties, and the ones you like and

01:04:56.756 --> 01:05:00.196
the ones that everybody likes, and they
have their temples and their offerings.

01:05:00.756 --> 01:05:04.336
It was very interesting to
me to go into a temple in

01:05:04.396 --> 01:05:08.316
Kolkata when I went there with
my wife, Joanna, we went into

01:05:09.316 --> 01:05:12.566
the temples and saw how they were, and I
think they must be very much like the ones in

01:05:12.596 --> 01:05:15.856
Mesopotamia. So there was never
anything about them which

01:05:15.996 --> 01:05:19.936
affronted people's individuality, or

01:05:19.996 --> 01:05:23.506
or, I mean, there's no religious
prejudice or even racial

01:05:23.596 --> 01:05:26.496
prejudice in antiquity. All
these things are modern

01:05:26.936 --> 01:05:30.576
disadvantageous matters. If you
think what's done in the name of

01:05:30.616 --> 01:05:33.816
religion, it is absolutely staggering.

01:05:33.876 --> 01:05:37.496
- So let's go to literature,
'cause we didn't really mention

01:05:37.536 --> 01:05:41.076
literature much, except you did
briefly mention Epic of Gilgamesh.

01:05:41.116 --> 01:05:45.116
So that was written in cuneiform. It's
one of the earliest works of literature.

01:05:45.156 --> 01:05:45.716
- That's right.

01:05:45.816 --> 01:05:47.476
- Can you tell me about this work?

01:05:47.516 --> 01:05:51.336
- Yeah. Well, we know it best from
this Assyrian library set of

01:05:51.396 --> 01:05:54.676
tablets. There are 12 of them. It's
a 12-tablet work, so it's quite

01:05:54.796 --> 01:05:58.706
long. And Gilgamesh is the hero of it.

01:05:58.736 --> 01:06:02.596
But the literature, we know
it from earlier texts.

01:06:02.636 --> 01:06:06.596
And we know that Gilgamesh lived.
He was a real person, he was a king

01:06:07.256 --> 01:06:10.916
in Uruk, and he was one
of those people who lived

01:06:11.056 --> 01:06:13.976
after their death in the
world, like Alexander, for

01:06:14.036 --> 01:06:17.876
example. So there were stories
about Gilgamesh when he was alive.

01:06:17.936 --> 01:06:21.616
There were stories about him
afterwards. And firstly, they were oral

01:06:21.656 --> 01:06:25.555
literature, not written down at all.

01:06:25.676 --> 01:06:29.575
And then around the 1800s, people
started to write them down in

01:06:29.616 --> 01:06:33.535
Sumerian or Babylonian. So there
was a corpus, and eventually

01:06:33.575 --> 01:06:37.356
they were woven into this long
12 Homeric-type thing about the

01:06:37.395 --> 01:06:41.096
adventures of Gilgamesh. So
it is certainly literature,

01:06:41.156 --> 01:06:48.075
and it's to do with humanity and immortality,
and man in the hands of the gods, and

01:06:48.455 --> 01:06:52.356
incorporates lots of interesting and exciting
stories. It's very Hollywoody kind of

01:06:52.395 --> 01:07:00.136
thing. And you can see within it, even in
the sophisticated Nineveh version, its

01:07:00.196 --> 01:07:03.596
roots are in oral literature.
Because when somebody speaks,

01:07:04.136 --> 01:07:07.676
it says, "Gilgamesh opened his mouth
to speak and addressed his friend

01:07:07.796 --> 01:07:11.645
Enkidu," and then there's a speech.
"And then Enkidu opened his mouth and

01:07:11.736 --> 01:07:15.575
addressed his friend Gilgamesh." Well,
when you're reading a story, you don't

01:07:15.636 --> 01:07:20.575
need that, and that must be because of when
there was an enacting of an oral thing,

01:07:21.415 --> 01:07:28.475
a narrator would say and it suddenly
got frozen into the text. So it's a

01:07:28.495 --> 01:07:32.256
very strange thing, because if you're
reading it, it's obvious that one person

01:07:32.296 --> 01:07:35.895
speaks and the other person
speaks, and they always have this

01:07:35.915 --> 01:07:39.455
complicated thing stuck in
the text. So it must be an

01:07:39.555 --> 01:07:46.216
echo of... presumably you have your
protagonists enacting their timeless

01:07:46.336 --> 01:07:50.055
matter with a... And the
person who's writing it

01:07:50.116 --> 01:07:54.676
down says, "And then Gilgamesh
said..." you know, like in a script.

01:07:55.356 --> 01:08:01.756
- I mean, what can you say about this,
the telling of stories in written form

01:08:01.995 --> 01:08:06.575
during that time? Do you think
that, too, stretched back in time?

01:08:06.716 --> 01:08:10.475
- I do. I think the fireside narrative

01:08:10.555 --> 01:08:14.136
matter. You know, when we were
kids it would be twerps with a

01:08:14.156 --> 01:08:18.076
guitar sitting around
a fire on holiday. But

01:08:18.215 --> 01:08:22.166
that mechanism, when people gather
after dark when there is a fire and

01:08:22.276 --> 01:08:25.456
talk, is the sort of environment where,

01:08:25.916 --> 01:08:30.036
narrative accounts flourish
naturally among human beings.

01:08:30.116 --> 01:08:33.505
- Stories, telling of story. It doesn't
have to be pragmatic, it could be--

01:08:33.505 --> 01:08:35.236
...literary in a way.

01:08:35.276 --> 01:08:38.956
- Yeah. Either a human
person like Gilgamesh or,

01:08:39.036 --> 01:08:42.965
stories about the gods, and
someone sees the Milky Way and

01:08:42.975 --> 01:08:46.486
they think, "There's a god riding a chariot
up it," and then they have a story about

01:08:46.515 --> 01:08:50.456
you know, and all those sorts of things.
Whatever it would be. But I think

01:08:51.135 --> 01:08:56.015
probably you have to allow
for a strong creative

01:08:56.935 --> 01:09:00.496
principle surfacing in homo
sapiens at a quite early

01:09:00.656 --> 01:09:04.706
age, because the paintings
on cave walls...

01:09:04.736 --> 01:09:08.696
You try drawing a running
antelope in color on a wall.

01:09:08.755 --> 01:09:13.956
I mean, the quality of the workmanship,
of the artistic ability, is

01:09:15.156 --> 01:09:18.755
unsurpassable. It's not just good. So,

01:09:19.116 --> 01:09:22.935
how is that an explicable thing
at this very early date? It means

01:09:24.335 --> 01:09:27.816
that among all the population,
you have imbeciles and

01:09:28.335 --> 01:09:32.295
Einsteins, and somewhere along
the line you have Rembrandts.

01:09:32.356 --> 01:09:36.295
And I imagine that half
the cave paintings in

01:09:36.356 --> 01:09:40.295
Europe were done by one person. I mean,
you get the impression every family

01:09:40.356 --> 01:09:44.276
had a genius painter. It's impossible. Probably
there was a person who went from place

01:09:44.295 --> 01:09:47.956
to place doing these paintings
because they were so... could draw

01:09:48.236 --> 01:09:51.935
straight away accurately
like that. But they are a

01:09:52.015 --> 01:09:55.755
distillation of creative artistic ability

01:09:55.835 --> 01:09:59.635
plus skill. So this is
right at the pretty early

01:09:59.755 --> 01:10:02.656
stage, is it not, the cave
painting material? So,

01:10:03.656 --> 01:10:09.496
if you consider the human stock which
encapsulates such ideas ever after,

01:10:10.635 --> 01:10:13.876
then you have to reckon with that.
You have to reckon with that. Very

01:10:13.936 --> 01:10:21.456
creative, very creative people. So the
function of stories to tell the young and

01:10:21.616 --> 01:10:25.056
about what happened and about
famous battles or when the flood

01:10:25.135 --> 01:10:32.635
came, or how people learned to
make fire, or you know, how we

01:10:32.656 --> 01:10:36.616
invented the wheel. All those sorts
of things everybody puts down as,

01:10:36.656 --> 01:10:40.016
but that's presumably what absolutely
happened. And you have the

01:10:40.096 --> 01:10:44.056
capacity for people to
adore and to respect

01:10:44.675 --> 01:10:48.236
among their own kind, people of
astounding ability. There must have

01:10:48.255 --> 01:10:52.196
been hunters who were
ferociously quick and,

01:10:52.215 --> 01:10:55.536
you know, wrestled with polar bears
and all that kind of thing. And

01:10:56.116 --> 01:10:59.856
all this stuff would be grist to the
narrator's thing. And as things got

01:10:59.916 --> 01:11:03.635
more complicated and more
sophisticated, so lessons might be

01:11:03.656 --> 01:11:07.536
incorporated or lessons might come
out of them unintentionally. Because

01:11:07.596 --> 01:11:11.236
if you tell a story without a
moral, there is usually a moral if

01:11:11.295 --> 01:11:13.635
you think about it.

01:11:13.675 --> 01:11:19.616
- And many of those stories are sadly
lost to time or not yet found.

01:11:19.675 --> 01:11:23.576
You mentioned floods, and speaking
of stories that have been

01:11:23.616 --> 01:11:27.416
lost and found, you're well-known
for a lot of things. One of them is

01:11:27.456 --> 01:11:29.736
decoding the so-called Ark Tablet.

01:11:29.795 --> 01:11:32.496
- Yeah. That was a challenge,
because it's really hard to read.

01:11:32.556 --> 01:11:39.116
- You've got to tell me the story. This
ancient Babylonian clay tablet dating 1700

01:11:39.135 --> 01:11:43.016
BC, which contains a flood
narrative that predates the

01:11:43.036 --> 01:11:45.436
biblical story of Noah
by a thousand years.

01:11:45.496 --> 01:11:46.295
- At least.

01:11:46.335 --> 01:11:50.276
- At least. Okay. Well, you
gotta tell me the full story.

01:11:50.295 --> 01:11:53.156
- So the full story is like this.
Visitors used to come to the

01:11:53.236 --> 01:11:56.956
museum to ask questions of the experts who

01:11:57.016 --> 01:12:00.696
worked there, and one would
be on duty periodically, and

01:12:00.755 --> 01:12:04.566
sometimes people would bring objects,
sometimes they'd ask questions. And somebody

01:12:04.656 --> 01:12:08.495
once came in with a whole load of objects,
including this tablet, which, to cut a long

01:12:08.556 --> 01:12:12.396
story short, I identified pretty
much straight away as being

01:12:12.456 --> 01:12:16.175
part of the flood story. It
was a tablet about eight

01:12:16.255 --> 01:12:20.135
inches by three. Not the whole
flood story, which is a complex

01:12:20.215 --> 01:12:23.996
narrative which ended up in the
Gilgamesh narrative much, much later,

01:12:24.776 --> 01:12:28.536
but this one was an early
narrative in which the point

01:12:28.576 --> 01:12:32.480
was taken up where the
gods in heaven had decided

01:12:32.490 --> 01:12:36.440
that the population of
Mesopotamia needed to be wiped

01:12:36.580 --> 01:12:40.519
out because they were so noisy.

01:12:40.540 --> 01:12:44.160
This was the expression. And
the gods couldn't sleep after

01:12:44.200 --> 01:12:47.879
lunch, sort of thing. So they decided
they would wipe them out and create

01:12:47.920 --> 01:12:55.009
something quieter that worked harder. So
this was the basic mechanism, and they had

01:12:55.019 --> 01:12:58.940
different ways of doing it. And then the most
effective one was they were going to send a

01:12:58.980 --> 01:13:02.320
flood to wipe them all out. And one
of the gods, the number three in the

01:13:02.559 --> 01:13:07.599
triumvirate, thought this was a deplorable
idea. So he took it upon himself to warn

01:13:08.440 --> 01:13:11.380
this person called
Atra-Hasis, who lived in

01:13:11.420 --> 01:13:19.110
Mesopotamia, to build a boat to rescue life
when the waters came. And in it, he told

01:13:19.160 --> 01:13:23.019
him the shape of it and the materials
he would need and how much he would

01:13:23.059 --> 01:13:24.040
need of the materials.

01:13:24.860 --> 01:13:28.790
So he could do it safely. And in the
60 lines of the tablet, all this

01:13:28.840 --> 01:13:32.559
stuff was there. It was like a
blueprint to build this boat. And

01:13:33.179 --> 01:13:36.110
it was just extraordinary
because it was round, the

01:13:36.160 --> 01:13:42.780
boat. And everybody who knew their
Bible, the ark's a coffin shape kind of

01:13:42.800 --> 01:13:47.540
affair. And nobody thought of
it being a round boat. And

01:13:49.280 --> 01:13:53.179
the fact is that round boats were

01:13:53.420 --> 01:13:57.040
used in Mesopotamia on the rivers,
coracles that's to say, because

01:13:57.719 --> 01:14:01.559
for transporting things, and they
would never sink. They were very

01:14:02.980 --> 01:14:06.910
appropriate. And so in this
story, it was decided it was

01:14:06.920 --> 01:14:10.710
going to be a giant coracle, a
really, really big one that would

01:14:10.719 --> 01:14:17.040
never sink, and the male and female
animals could go in and Atra-Hasis'

01:14:17.099 --> 01:14:21.070
wife and his three sons and so forth,
could go in and everything would be there

01:14:21.080 --> 01:14:22.420
and it would float on the water.

01:14:23.320 --> 01:14:26.240
And when it came down, they said,
"We'll start all over again." So

01:14:26.980 --> 01:14:30.160
it's got very many points
in common with the

01:14:30.580 --> 01:14:34.340
description of the flood in Genesis. And
of course, so did the one in Gilgamesh. So

01:14:34.500 --> 01:14:42.179
in 1872, there was a serologist in
the British Museum called George

01:14:42.219 --> 01:14:45.679
Smith, and he was a very, very talented

01:14:45.759 --> 01:14:49.500
reader. And in 1872, he
discovered that one of the

01:14:49.540 --> 01:14:53.420
tablets from the Nineveh library
we were talking about before

01:14:53.460 --> 01:14:57.440
had on it a passage which ran
in parallel with Gilgamesh

01:14:58.320 --> 01:15:01.719
about the waters coming
and the boat and everybody

01:15:01.780 --> 01:15:05.440
floating. And even to
the point that when the

01:15:05.639 --> 01:15:09.559
rain stopped and the ark came
to rest on a mountain, that

01:15:09.639 --> 01:15:12.500
the hero of this thing in
Gilgamesh, who was called

01:15:12.620 --> 01:15:16.400
Utnapishtim, released a bird three

01:15:16.460 --> 01:15:20.370
times to see whether the trees had come
up, and the first one came back and

01:15:20.380 --> 01:15:23.590
the second one, and the third one
didn't. So he knew that... So this

01:15:23.660 --> 01:15:26.840
was not only in the Epic of

01:15:27.120 --> 01:15:30.940
Gilgamesh, but it was also in the
book of Genesis. So what it meant

01:15:31.040 --> 01:15:33.460
was that it wasn't...
You couldn't have two

01:15:33.540 --> 01:15:40.340
stories... It wasn't two stories about the
same thing. It was literary dependence.

01:15:40.460 --> 01:15:44.420
It was literary dependence. One was locked
into the other. The text of the Hebrew

01:15:44.429 --> 01:15:48.370
Bible from whenever it was written down, of
course, nobody knows quite when, but whenever it

01:15:48.480 --> 01:15:52.410
was, it was about the
same time as the one from

01:15:52.420 --> 01:15:56.259
Nineveh, about the 7th century,
6th century, something like that.

01:15:56.460 --> 01:15:59.980
The time interval between
the Gilgamesh version from

01:16:00.019 --> 01:16:03.380
Nineveh and the Hebrew Bible
is not like a big expanse of

01:16:03.500 --> 01:16:07.309
time. So there was an argument that
one goes this way and one goes that

01:16:07.340 --> 01:16:10.300
way. But then when this tablet
came in, a thousand years

01:16:10.719 --> 01:16:18.240
older, nobody believes the Bible was
written in 1700 BC. So the primacy of the

01:16:18.280 --> 01:16:25.170
Mesopotamian matter was established. And
it's important because you never get

01:16:25.179 --> 01:16:29.150
floods in Jerusalem. You just don't.

01:16:29.160 --> 01:16:33.120
But in Mesopotamia, they had floods. The
rivers, sometimes there wasn't enough

01:16:33.139 --> 01:16:37.080
water, sometimes there was too much,
sometimes there was far too much water.

01:16:37.139 --> 01:16:40.960
So the mechanism that the waters
could be used as a destructive force

01:16:41.019 --> 01:16:44.540
by the powers that be is
a plausible Mesopotamian

01:16:44.620 --> 01:16:48.480
mechanism and is based in
a sort of sense, in my

01:16:48.519 --> 01:16:52.259
opinion, in reality. I think
there must have been some tsunami

01:16:52.320 --> 01:16:56.040
once most people were drowned and
those who survived were in boats,

01:16:56.099 --> 01:16:59.309
obviously. And then afterwards,
nobody ever forgot it.

01:17:00.440 --> 01:17:01.389
And it went on and on and on.

01:17:01.389 --> 01:17:04.889
- So, you mean there actually could have been
a catastrophic event of a large scale?

01:17:04.900 --> 01:17:07.309
- Yeah, not the whole world,
because people were-

01:17:07.309 --> 01:17:08.870
- But just enough to imagine.

01:17:08.920 --> 01:17:12.860
- Yeah, sweeping down to the Persian Gulf and,
you know, the flat plains, everything would be

01:17:12.870 --> 01:17:16.570
destroyed, all the houses would be
destroyed, animals would be drowned and...

01:17:16.580 --> 01:17:20.040
- This is an incredible discovery. Do you
think it's possible that this is the

01:17:20.080 --> 01:17:24.420
original? There are flood
myths in many cultures.

01:17:24.429 --> 01:17:32.059
- I believe this. The Mesopotamians had a
deep-seated horror of dependency on water

01:17:32.260 --> 01:17:38.299
when they couldn't control it. They were
fearful of it. And they had a rainbow in

01:17:38.320 --> 01:17:42.299
Babylonia, like in the Bible,
as a proof that the disastrous

01:17:42.340 --> 01:17:45.880
flood would never happen again. But
I think there must have been one

01:17:45.960 --> 01:17:48.679
episode of this kind, maybe

01:17:49.620 --> 01:17:53.530
5,000 years before the tablet, 10,000,
it doesn't matter. Because with the

01:17:53.530 --> 01:17:57.120
passage of time, nothing happens in that
part of the world. So something will be

01:17:57.200 --> 01:18:00.929
alive, grandfather to grandson,
before you go to sleep, "And

01:18:00.960 --> 01:18:04.480
remember, my boy, you know, you
only have to be careful because

01:18:04.559 --> 01:18:08.120
otherwise..." and all that
stuff. For sure, bogeyman

01:18:08.260 --> 01:18:13.120
stuff. It never quite died out
in their conscious minds. So

01:18:14.160 --> 01:18:17.980
I think that when the
Judeans from Jerusalem,

01:18:18.040 --> 01:18:21.980
after the destruction of the
temple by the Babylonians and the

01:18:22.099 --> 01:18:25.980
rout of the priesthood and everything,
the king and the others went over

01:18:26.040 --> 01:18:29.960
land to Babylon as refugees,
and they had to live there

01:18:30.000 --> 01:18:33.160
for three generations of time
under Nebuchadnezzar's reign.

01:18:33.219 --> 01:18:37.099
So I believe that the text
of the Bible was written

01:18:37.160 --> 01:18:41.000
then, because if you read the
Bible attentively, which I

01:18:41.780 --> 01:18:44.990
can't say I do on a regular basis, but
if you do read it dispassionately,

01:18:45.860 --> 01:18:49.639
you have the mechanism that the
only books that the Bible explain

01:18:49.959 --> 01:18:53.260
to the reader how it is that
these people are in such a

01:18:53.360 --> 01:18:57.260
mess. Because they're supposed
to be the chosen people

01:18:57.719 --> 01:19:01.599
doing all that. And, look, they haven't got a
temple, they haven't got a country, they're washed

01:19:01.700 --> 01:19:06.580
up and everything like that. So
I think that what happened was

01:19:07.780 --> 01:19:11.139
it's, it's a complex thing,
but the Judeans from

01:19:11.200 --> 01:19:14.519
Jerusalem, they spoke
Hebrew, but they also spoke

01:19:14.580 --> 01:19:18.200
Aramaic, right? The two languages,
they're sister languages. And the

01:19:18.240 --> 01:19:22.230
Babylonians spoke Babylonian,
and they also spoke Aramaic. And

01:19:22.260 --> 01:19:26.160
they all wore the same kind of clothes,
and they all had brown skin. And

01:19:26.200 --> 01:19:29.960
when all these refugees
from Jerusalem were milling

01:19:30.040 --> 01:19:33.719
around in Babylonia, they
would have intermarried and

01:19:33.740 --> 01:19:37.540
disappeared within no time
at all. And the authorities

01:19:37.620 --> 01:19:45.059
who were there prevented this by drawing
up a kind of charter of their history,

01:19:45.080 --> 01:19:48.099
explaining things from the
beginning of time up until

01:19:48.240 --> 01:19:52.630
now, how it happened and what
happened, and it was all intentional.

01:19:53.620 --> 01:19:57.250
So that is, in my opinion, the
driving force behind the Hebrew

01:19:57.320 --> 01:20:00.740
text. And the thing about
it is that they didn't

01:20:00.840 --> 01:20:04.820
have in Jewish philosophical
tradition stuff about

01:20:04.840 --> 01:20:08.440
creation and the beginning
of the world. And they

01:20:08.519 --> 01:20:12.440
took Babylonian ideas, which
they learnt when they were

01:20:12.519 --> 01:20:14.780
there, and they recycled them.

01:20:16.580 --> 01:20:20.380
So whereas the Babylonians
decided that the gods were gonna

01:20:20.440 --> 01:20:24.080
wipe out the noisy
persons, when the Jewish

01:20:24.099 --> 01:20:27.900
philosophers got this
narrative to recycle about,

01:20:27.920 --> 01:20:31.809
about the vengeful Almighty in the
Old Testament a very unpleasant and

01:20:31.860 --> 01:20:35.780
vengeful person, it was because of
sin. It wasn't because of rocket

01:20:35.800 --> 01:20:39.700
and playing the radio, it
was sin. So they took one

01:20:39.800 --> 01:20:43.880
narrative and they recycled
it for their own purposes.

01:20:43.920 --> 01:20:49.219
- The flood is a useful tool to
punish people for whatever X is?

01:20:49.280 --> 01:20:53.080
- That's exactly right. And something
else is this. Something else is

01:20:53.120 --> 01:20:57.019
this, right? You have five days to build
the ark or whatever it is, or two weeks to

01:20:57.040 --> 01:21:00.830
build the ark, so the clock goes
tick, tick, tick, tick, tick. And

01:21:00.940 --> 01:21:04.940
about a third of the films that come out
of Hollywood are the world's gonna be

01:21:05.780 --> 01:21:09.750
demolished by aliens, and you've got 24
hours to think of a cure, tick, tick, tick,

01:21:09.760 --> 01:21:13.059
tick, tick, tick, tick. So
it's the... that narrative is

01:21:13.139 --> 01:21:17.080
irresistible, that one
man can save the world,

01:21:17.160 --> 01:21:21.139
if he's lucky, in time from
disaster. So it starts off with

01:21:21.200 --> 01:21:26.120
Utnapishtim, and then it goes on to
Noah, and then it goes on to Hollywood.

01:21:27.200 --> 01:21:33.540
- Do you think this ark in the tablet
actually was ever built? You did

01:21:33.860 --> 01:21:36.480
build a replica one third the size.

01:21:36.500 --> 01:21:40.400
And people should check out, you
tell the story of that wonderfully.

01:21:40.460 --> 01:21:44.099
What did you learn from building
this replica? And do you think the

01:21:44.179 --> 01:21:46.050
actual ark existed?

01:21:46.059 --> 01:21:49.920
- No, I don't think so. I think it's
a literary construction out of the

01:21:49.980 --> 01:21:53.059
reality that people who
did survive were on boats.

01:21:53.320 --> 01:21:57.300
I mean, they had boats for
sure, and you might wake up

01:21:57.340 --> 01:22:03.440
in the Persian Gulf and never know what
happened, but, you know, it's a literary

01:22:04.360 --> 01:22:08.200
moral principle teaching
narrative. And look, missionaries

01:22:08.260 --> 01:22:12.170
take it all around the world. That's
the other thing. See, there...

01:22:12.200 --> 01:22:15.840
this is, this is the mystery of it,
that you have flood stories everywhere,

01:22:16.240 --> 01:22:20.160
and some of them are from meddlesome missionaries
who have all these innocent little kids

01:22:20.200 --> 01:22:24.009
sitting on benches and, "I'm
going to tell you a story."

01:22:24.380 --> 01:22:27.960
like that. So it moves into this consciousness,
then it gets recycled and it gets

01:22:28.019 --> 01:22:31.440
recycled. So this is one thing.
And then also, there probably are

01:22:31.740 --> 01:22:35.620
spontaneous ideas, because
it's not so complicated

01:22:35.679 --> 01:22:39.509
or so amazing that independently people
would have such a narrative. After

01:22:39.559 --> 01:22:43.450
all, you know, like the great river
in China floods and everybody gets...

01:22:43.460 --> 01:22:47.200
so that, that's not at all surprising.
But what was so shocking for George

01:22:47.280 --> 01:22:51.148
Smith, who was such a clever
person, is to read for the

01:22:51.259 --> 01:22:54.639
first time on this tablet
from Nineveh, long

01:22:54.740 --> 01:22:58.679
before the one that I discovered
came to light, about the three

01:22:58.780 --> 01:23:02.700
birds being released one after
the other. And that, that was

01:23:02.760 --> 01:23:06.648
the clincher that the two stories
were locked together. And lots of

01:23:06.679 --> 01:23:10.599
clergymen got very miserable about it
and didn't know what to make of it.

01:23:10.660 --> 01:23:13.360
- So that's, that's a definitive
proof that those are liter-

01:23:13.420 --> 01:23:18.280
- A literary, I think
literary link. I think so.

01:23:18.360 --> 01:23:23.740
- And I mean, these puzzles that are then
connected, but the ark, you discor-

01:23:24.620 --> 01:23:32.019
1,000 years. So that means that
story of the flood has been

01:23:32.099 --> 01:23:37.340
told many, many times across
that span to, you know-

01:23:37.540 --> 01:23:40.209
... "Do your homework or
the flood is gonna come."

01:23:40.240 --> 01:23:40.740
- That's right.

01:23:40.800 --> 01:23:42.460
- Do all that can... oh.

01:23:42.519 --> 01:23:46.460
- That's right. And every time
somebody built a coracle and they

01:23:46.519 --> 01:23:49.440
didn't do the waterproofing right,

01:23:49.480 --> 01:23:53.460
you know what will happen? You'll be out on
the river and that will be your lot, you know?

01:23:53.500 --> 01:23:56.880
I, I think so. I think it was a...
I, I... there's a certain amount of

01:23:56.960 --> 01:24:04.620
evidence that in Mesopotamian society,
people talk about the time before the flood

01:24:05.559 --> 01:24:09.219
and after the flood. And
it's like when I was a

01:24:09.260 --> 01:24:16.030
boy, people used to talk about, "Before
the war, we used to..." And now,

01:24:16.059 --> 01:24:23.620
we, we do this. It's, it's a kind of
cataclysmic cut across history which provides

01:24:23.700 --> 01:24:27.380
a, a, a ruler, so things are
either before it or after

01:24:27.420 --> 01:24:31.260
it. Because there's a king
list, for example, where they

01:24:31.280 --> 01:24:35.110
wrote down the names of all the kings, all the way
back to the beginning, including kings before the

01:24:35.240 --> 01:24:39.027
flood. They knew about that... they
have their names and their great

01:24:39.108 --> 01:24:42.308
regnal years, or thousands
of years. Fascinating.

01:24:42.367 --> 01:24:45.827
- So there's a guy named Graham Hancock
who talks about the Younger Dryas

01:24:45.867 --> 01:24:53.608
hypothesis, 10,000 BC, that there was an
asteroid that hit Earth and melted the ice

01:24:53.688 --> 01:24:57.348
sheets, and that created a
flood in North America. So that

01:24:57.388 --> 01:25:01.188
means an actual cataclysmic
global event, that

01:25:01.288 --> 01:25:04.928
then as all the different
civilizations sprang up,

01:25:05.148 --> 01:25:09.008
they all carried that knowledge, that

01:25:09.068 --> 01:25:13.148
memory. That's his idea. What
probability would you assign to that?

01:25:13.248 --> 01:25:18.128
- I would say negligible, because I
regard it as a literary matter,

01:25:18.137 --> 01:25:22.027
which is not predicated on the
existence of flood in people's

01:25:22.148 --> 01:25:26.137
minds. But I do believe that
the story in Mesopotamia owes

01:25:26.188 --> 01:25:30.617
its inception to a disastrous
flood, but nothing global.

01:25:30.628 --> 01:25:34.088
Nothing that touched America
or China or Birmingham. So

01:25:34.568 --> 01:25:37.928
But people have made drilled cores and then they... I do
that all the... I'm not interested in all that stuff.

01:25:38.168 --> 01:25:42.978
I do that all the... I'm not interested
in all that stuff. It's, to my mind...

01:25:42.978 --> 01:25:43.338
- It's a literary device.

01:25:43.367 --> 01:25:46.947
- It's a literary top-off of great potency,

01:25:47.068 --> 01:25:50.708
of irresistible potency, because
everybody identifies with the idea

01:25:51.088 --> 01:25:54.947
of being in bed and someone knocks on the
door, says, "Get up, you got to build a boat,

01:25:55.008 --> 01:25:58.628
and this is what you're going to need, and you
got to get on with it, sunshine, or we're all

01:25:58.688 --> 01:26:02.608
sunk." I mean, what are you going to
do? The most interesting thing is

01:26:02.668 --> 01:26:07.668
this Atrahasis in the 1700 text. He wasn't a
king and he wasn't a sailor or a boat builder.

01:26:08.588 --> 01:26:12.527
and he wasn't a sailor or a boat
builder. So, how comes this clever god

01:26:12.628 --> 01:26:16.588
who wants to find someone to
build... Wouldn't you go for a look

01:26:16.628 --> 01:26:20.487
in the Yellow Pages for a boat-building
company, say, "Listen, fellow, I got a deal..."

01:26:20.508 --> 01:26:24.178
No. He had to tell him, "This is the blueprint, this
is the shape, you need all this, you need all that,

01:26:24.248 --> 01:26:27.907
you need all this, you need all that,
you got to measure it and all that."

01:26:28.468 --> 01:26:30.688
It's a very interesting thing.

01:26:30.728 --> 01:26:35.108
- I mean, yeah, that's a great story. You
don't go to the great boat builder, go-

01:26:35.648 --> 01:26:36.878
- Taxi driver or something like that.

01:26:36.878 --> 01:26:40.827
- To the taxi, and then
that's that hero's journey.

01:26:40.848 --> 01:26:43.428
That's the stuff of great myths, yeah.

01:26:43.487 --> 01:26:45.188
- It is. It is a great myth.

01:26:45.288 --> 01:26:49.128
- A little detail would be really
cool about the replica, like...

01:26:49.248 --> 01:26:49.257
- Of the boat?

01:26:49.257 --> 01:26:51.898
- What did you... Of the boat, yeah.
One-third replica, of course.

01:26:51.898 --> 01:26:57.148
- That was something else. There
were three blokes who did it.

01:26:57.188 --> 01:27:03.237
And they were specialists in
reconstructing medieval Arab boats.

01:27:03.288 --> 01:27:07.268
Because quite often, they're found in the
mud or bits, or they have information.

01:27:07.308 --> 01:27:11.168
So they were at home in it. And we
built it on a small lagoon in Kerala.

01:27:11.228 --> 01:27:15.188
in a small lagoon in Kerala. It was just
the most unbelievably wonderful thing,

01:27:15.248 --> 01:27:19.208
the most unbelievably wonderful thing, because
they used the instructions as a blueprint.

01:27:19.228 --> 01:27:22.987
They made it about a third of the size
of the original, a pretty huge thing.

01:27:23.068 --> 01:27:27.668
But they made it because it
had wooden ribs, you see?

01:27:28.068 --> 01:27:31.388
And they could get wood ribs. They worked out
by computer the maximum size they could do it

01:27:31.468 --> 01:27:35.348
the maximum size they could do it when it
would work. Beyond it, it would be impossible,

01:27:35.367 --> 01:27:39.228
Beyond it, it would be impossible,
because once they built the curved ribs,

01:27:39.288 --> 01:27:43.268
and then they stuffed woven all around it,

01:27:43.327 --> 01:27:46.947
it had to be covered in bitumen, which is
also very heavy, to make it waterproof.

01:27:46.987 --> 01:27:50.508
So they calculated the
size, and it worked.

01:27:50.568 --> 01:27:54.468
So they built this thing on rollers and
it was pushed out into the... It was just

01:27:54.487 --> 01:27:58.388
just the most unbelievable... I went out there
with my dear wife for the last few days,

01:27:58.428 --> 01:28:02.108
and was on the maiden voyage. And they had
trouble with the bitumen, because Indian bitumen

01:28:02.148 --> 01:28:05.527
because Indian bitumen is
really not up to scratch.

01:28:05.608 --> 01:28:09.527
And they couldn't get Iraqi bitumen, because
its cultural property is carcinogenic.

01:28:09.568 --> 01:28:13.468
They wouldn't export a tanker load of
Iraqi. So we had to use the Indian stuff.

01:28:13.527 --> 01:28:17.327
But the thing is this, the bitumen which they
coated it with was okay, but it wasn't perfect.

01:28:17.367 --> 01:28:21.208
So when it went out...

01:28:21.268 --> 01:28:25.768
into the waters, there was a bit of
a leak, water had to be bailed out.

01:28:25.827 --> 01:28:29.088
So, they said, "Ah," you see,
and I said, I s- I said,

01:28:29.097 --> 01:28:32.907
"Okay, listen, sunshine," I said to this
producer, "You ever been in a rowing

01:28:32.968 --> 01:28:35.808
boat without water in
the bottom? Excuse me?"

01:28:35.888 --> 01:28:37.458
- Oh, you're saying that's
a feature, not a bug.

01:28:37.468 --> 01:28:40.737
- That's the feature of the thing,
yeah. That's the feature.

01:28:40.748 --> 01:28:41.968
That thing could've gone to ports.

01:28:41.987 --> 01:28:43.068
- So it's authentic.

01:28:43.208 --> 01:28:46.668
- Absolutely right. We had
such an adventure with that

01:28:46.708 --> 01:28:50.348
thing. They made a documentary film.

01:28:50.527 --> 01:28:54.468
in various languages. And you know
what they did? You know, I was in it

01:28:54.528 --> 01:28:58.507
a bit- a bit, and they had people saying,
"Oh, I don't think it was this, I

01:28:58.528 --> 01:29:01.768
don't think it was that," you know, and they didn't let
me go back and say, "What the hell are you talking about?

01:29:01.907 --> 01:29:05.888
I did it, I know what... I can read, you know,
... you." They didn't have, they didn't do

01:29:05.947 --> 01:29:10.208
it. I- I couldn't get my own back. I
was really annoyed. Really furious.

01:29:10.268 --> 01:29:13.438
- So you're saying that there are
some inaccurate things to it.

01:29:13.567 --> 01:29:17.428
- I am saying there are some inaccurate
things. Yeah, somebody in Iraq said, "Oh, it

01:29:17.447 --> 01:29:21.148
couldn't have been that, they probably had lots
of little coracles all tied together." Did they

01:29:21.447 --> 01:29:25.028
f*ck? I mean, I, you know, he couldn't
read the stuff. I mean, it's really,

01:29:25.067 --> 01:29:28.947
really, really annoying. I mean, you should have
a chance, shouldn't you? You know, if you're

01:29:28.968 --> 01:29:32.188
gonna have a fencing match, you both
have to have a rapier, wouldn't you say?

01:29:32.268 --> 01:29:37.067
- Yeah, and you're the OG. You're
the person that decoded it.

01:29:37.077 --> 01:29:40.788
- Well, I can read. Yeah. But the thing
is this, the proportions of the

01:29:40.827 --> 01:29:47.577
material were accurate. This is
the crucial thing, that, um-

01:29:47.577 --> 01:29:51.487
what had happened was, is they took
the information about how you make

01:29:51.567 --> 01:29:56.388
a real coracle, which is usually enough,
two people- ...and a few sheep and goats-

01:29:56.428 --> 01:29:56.617
- Got it

01:29:56.617 --> 01:30:01.298
- ...and they bumped them up- ...so
that it worked. And I know why that

01:30:01.327 --> 01:30:05.188
is, because it goes back
to your question about

01:30:05.268 --> 01:30:08.308
oral literature, because
there must have been times

01:30:08.348 --> 01:30:11.788
when people went to villages
and told them about the

01:30:11.808 --> 01:30:15.268
flood, and when they got
to the question of the

01:30:15.348 --> 01:30:18.987
boat, they'd say something
like this, "And Enki

01:30:19.088 --> 01:30:23.008
said, 'You've got to build the biggest
coracle you've ever seen.'" Like

01:30:23.067 --> 01:30:27.048
that, right? Well, I mean, if you
do this in a cinema in Guildford,

01:30:27.088 --> 01:30:30.768
people will say, "Well, that's fine,"
but if you do it to a whole load

01:30:30.888 --> 01:30:34.567
of river people who use coracles and make

01:30:34.748 --> 01:30:38.708
build, they're not gonna take that, they're
not... "So how big was it then? Come on, how

01:30:38.748 --> 01:30:42.447
big was it?" So what do they
do? They go to a coracle

01:30:42.728 --> 01:30:46.712
place and they work out the
proportions of material.

01:30:46.832 --> 01:30:50.552
and then they bump it up so that
the actor who reads this, for the

01:30:50.612 --> 01:30:54.372
first few times, he has in his pocket how
much it is. But after a while, he knows it by

01:30:54.432 --> 01:30:58.372
heart so that none of these people
get angry. "You can't expect us,

01:30:58.412 --> 01:31:02.372
big enough for all this." So then he'd
have all the stuff and he'd do it

01:31:02.392 --> 01:31:06.212
this way, "And you need all this, and
you need all this," and they'd all be

01:31:06.272 --> 01:31:10.202
hypnotized by it. That, I
think is, it's actually,

01:31:10.252 --> 01:31:13.652
regarding your question,
it's on the cusp of

01:31:13.712 --> 01:31:17.412
purely oral literature to purely literary

01:31:18.112 --> 01:31:22.032
literature. It's actually
there because you can see that

01:31:22.112 --> 01:31:26.532
it was molded in the environment
when people were still talking.

01:31:26.572 --> 01:31:29.272
- Yeah, you gotta make it authentic
to really connect with people.

01:31:29.392 --> 01:31:32.132
- Well, you couldn't pull it w- over
their eyes. I mean, you know?

01:31:32.142 --> 01:31:36.052
- Yeah, well, I wish many of the films
in Hollywood today would have the

01:31:36.092 --> 01:31:37.052
same level of rigor.

01:31:37.112 --> 01:31:40.152
- Rigor is one of the things
lacking in the world.

01:31:40.172 --> 01:31:45.732
- By the way, I forgot to ask, why was
the flood myth focused on noisy people?

01:31:45.742 --> 01:31:49.622
- Well, it can't really be noisy. I'll
tell you what the explanation is, it's-

01:31:49.652 --> 01:31:56.782
it's something quite different. Before the
flood, the gods had not created death.

01:31:58.672 --> 01:32:02.572
So I think the noise was a
reflex of the fact there

01:32:02.592 --> 01:32:06.092
were just too many
animals, too many people,

01:32:06.152 --> 01:32:09.282
and they had to do something
about it. So it's a sort of

01:32:09.332 --> 01:32:13.252
euphemism, so to speak,
because after the flood, at

01:32:13.312 --> 01:32:16.572
the end of the tablet... Not my tablet,
but the other ones, where it's still

01:32:16.632 --> 01:32:21.472
broken. It says, there's a
tantalizing thing where they create

01:32:22.512 --> 01:32:26.472
barren women and who can't have children
and men who can't have children

01:32:26.592 --> 01:32:29.872
and people who... Princesses who
don't have children, and they

01:32:29.952 --> 01:32:33.792
institute in society some figures who

01:32:33.912 --> 01:32:37.532
will not reproduce the species.
So it's actually a rather

01:32:37.592 --> 01:32:41.292
sophisticated Malthusian
kind of philosophical

01:32:41.372 --> 01:32:45.312
position. It's remarkable. So that
the noise means there's so many of

01:32:45.372 --> 01:32:50.552
them, not that they're actually so noisy
that we can't hear ourselves think.

01:32:50.712 --> 01:32:52.612
- You have to tell me about the-

01:32:53.812 --> 01:32:57.732
the world of ancient games. Maybe we can
start with the ancient Royal Game of

01:32:57.932 --> 01:33:05.412
Ur. What is it and how were you
somehow able to crack the rules of it?

01:33:05.432 --> 01:33:11.651
- Well, the Royal Game of Ur is a board
of 20 squares in a rather idiosyncratic

01:33:12.172 --> 01:33:19.932
form. And it was pretty much unknown
until the 1920s when Sir Leonard Woolley

01:33:19.952 --> 01:33:26.012
was digging at the site of Ur, and in
the graves of the royal family, Sumerian

01:33:26.052 --> 01:33:33.112
rulers, they found four or five boards
of this pattern, together with dice and

01:33:33.232 --> 01:33:39.472
pieces, which showed that it was popular
among them at this time, and also that

01:33:40.412 --> 01:33:43.222
wherever they were going in the world
to come, they would want to be playing

01:33:43.272 --> 01:33:49.992
it. And so that was one thing, and
we had the number of pieces and some

01:33:50.012 --> 01:33:53.842
dice. So lots of people
had ideas about how

01:33:53.892 --> 01:33:57.652
it might have been played, and
that went on like that for a

01:33:57.732 --> 01:34:01.602
very long time. And
thereafter, boards for this

01:34:01.632 --> 01:34:04.852
game turned up in most of
the countries of the Middle

01:34:04.932 --> 01:34:12.132
East, sometimes quite a lot of them. And-
and the one from Ur dates to about 2600

01:34:12.212 --> 01:34:18.572
BC, and from then down to the end
of the first millennium, there's

01:34:18.972 --> 01:34:26.672
examples of boards from Mesopotamia itself
and from Egypt Syria, Lebanon, Jordan,

01:34:26.732 --> 01:34:34.432
Turkey, Greece, Crete, all over the
place. When you put all the boards

01:34:34.442 --> 01:34:42.092
together, you realize that you're dealing
with a board game which was extremely

01:34:42.112 --> 01:34:44.792
widespread and extremely popular.

01:34:44.872 --> 01:34:46.432
- Across space and time.

01:34:46.492 --> 01:34:50.172
- across space and time. So it
lasted for nearly 3,000 years

01:34:50.772 --> 01:34:57.132
and it was played all over the place. So
it's one of those games which is like

01:34:57.992 --> 01:35:02.532
chess or backgammon, which
you can say are world

01:35:02.592 --> 01:35:10.212
conquerors. Because the way I see
the issue is that human beings,

01:35:10.292 --> 01:35:16.892
for a very long time, have
been, shall we say, hungry for

01:35:18.512 --> 01:35:23.832
things to do, because all through the
Bronze Age and the Iron Age, there was no

01:35:23.872 --> 01:35:29.842
television, you know? There was
nothing, and kids played with pull

01:35:29.912 --> 01:35:35.712
along things and adults had board games
and they're kind of embedded in culture

01:35:36.852 --> 01:35:40.612
from a very early time. And this game was

01:35:40.672 --> 01:35:44.632
so widespread. You know,
Tutankhamun, for example, in his

01:35:44.732 --> 01:35:48.712
tomb, there were two or three boards
for it with the pieces. So it arrived

01:35:48.772 --> 01:35:52.622
in the middle of the second
millennium in Egypt and

01:35:52.672 --> 01:35:56.332
even the Pharaoh played it. So you
have a game, which the interesting

01:35:56.452 --> 01:36:03.462
point about it is that it
spread across the known world

01:36:04.152 --> 01:36:11.612
without written rules and without people
necessarily knowing the same language.

01:36:11.672 --> 01:36:18.752
So a merchant would go, end up in a bar,
you know, come from India, or I don't know

01:36:18.792 --> 01:36:22.612
where, start seeing these guys playing,
have a go himself, and it looks

01:36:22.692 --> 01:36:26.382
rather interesting. You go home and try and remember
what it looked like and try to work out how

01:36:26.412 --> 01:36:30.082
to, you know, be transported
this way and the other. And

01:36:31.272 --> 01:36:35.152
so you can see that the board has 20
squares. So you have a block of four

01:36:35.192 --> 01:36:38.552
by three and then a bridge
of two and then a second

01:36:39.152 --> 01:36:42.552
three by two thing at the end. So

01:36:42.832 --> 01:36:46.610
it's difficult to describe the
actual shape. But what happened was

01:36:46.780 --> 01:36:53.839
after about 2000 BC, the squares at
the far end, which were two on one

01:36:54.620 --> 01:36:58.219
flank and two on the other,
were all put at the end of the

01:36:58.259 --> 01:37:01.700
central avenue. So you end
up with 12 squares down the

01:37:01.739 --> 01:37:05.630
middle. So all the boards
after the period of Ur have

01:37:05.639 --> 01:37:09.420
12 squares down the middle, and
then four on each side at one end.

01:37:09.440 --> 01:37:13.339
Mm. So it meant then that when you
play the game, you have dice to move

01:37:13.380 --> 01:37:18.219
the pieces, you have pieces all the
same, and you obviously put them on

01:37:19.120 --> 01:37:22.870
your first corner and you turn the corner
and you go up the middle and off the end.

01:37:22.960 --> 01:37:26.440
And it was a race game of the kind that
everybody knows from their own childhood.

01:37:26.580 --> 01:37:30.500
And some squares which had rosettes
on were either safe squares or

01:37:30.540 --> 01:37:34.299
you had another throw, and you
could maybe put two on one

01:37:34.360 --> 01:37:37.580
square, we don't know. You
could try and block people. But

01:37:37.620 --> 01:37:41.290
anyway, the crucial thing
is that the widespread

01:37:41.980 --> 01:37:45.860
distribution of this idiosyncratic
shape, and it's a lasting thing,

01:37:45.900 --> 01:37:52.700
shows it must have been a very good game,
if people more or less played the same

01:37:52.740 --> 01:37:56.400
thing on it everywhere. I mean, it may
be that they were completely different

01:37:56.440 --> 01:38:00.299
games, but probably not. So
this is the thing, it makes

01:38:00.360 --> 01:38:03.960
you wonder what it is about
it that would fit so well

01:38:04.320 --> 01:38:07.799
with a wide appetite from different
persons, different types of

01:38:07.860 --> 01:38:14.120
person. And the thing is that although it's
a race game where you're at the mercy of

01:38:14.440 --> 01:38:19.440
dice and lucky squares
and unlucky squares, the

01:38:19.740 --> 01:38:26.240
process of getting your pieces on and
off the board as a winner is primarily

01:38:26.299 --> 01:38:34.080
fortuitous. But it has built within it,
is the way I understand the game plays, a

01:38:34.299 --> 01:38:38.179
measurable quota of
strategy. It's a mix of

01:38:38.219 --> 01:38:41.880
probability and strategy.
So most games are

01:38:41.980 --> 01:38:45.920
either just probability
like Snakes and Ladders,

01:38:45.960 --> 01:38:49.940
like Chutes and Ladders is just a thing
like that. Or you have a game like chess,

01:38:49.980 --> 01:38:53.940
which is pure strategy. It's a mix.
And the grownup game in the modern

01:38:54.019 --> 01:38:57.160
world where fortuity or chance and

01:38:57.240 --> 01:39:01.080
strategy have a good balance is
backgammon, which is a sort of

01:39:01.139 --> 01:39:05.099
grownup version of this sort
of game. Where nevertheless,

01:39:05.160 --> 01:39:08.900
if you play according to the most
rational interpretation, its

01:39:08.940 --> 01:39:12.750
strategy is a major factor.
So what happened was that

01:39:12.960 --> 01:39:16.920
many people had ideas how it was played,
and the route followed, and I did too.

01:39:16.940 --> 01:39:20.110
And then I discovered this tablet
in the British Museum, which was

01:39:20.120 --> 01:39:27.759
written at a very late period in
the second century BC. So 2,300

01:39:27.769 --> 01:39:31.679
years after this object
existed, and it had on it

01:39:31.740 --> 01:39:35.540
the names of the pieces and
what the pieces were like and

01:39:35.620 --> 01:39:39.519
various things about the throws.
And it was obvious that it was,

01:39:40.440 --> 01:39:44.219
the rules were to do with a game
which was derived from this

01:39:44.280 --> 01:39:47.920
simple early game. And that
working backwards from

01:39:48.000 --> 01:39:51.860
it, you could reconstruct the
game in accordance with its later

01:39:51.940 --> 01:39:55.900
incarnation that might be workable.
And it jolly well turned out

01:39:55.940 --> 01:39:59.799
to be workable because people
play this all over the world now.

01:39:59.860 --> 01:40:03.820
And they even play in Iraq in cafes.

01:40:03.839 --> 01:40:07.820
Wait, now? They do. Oh, wow. Because
after it's come back to life, it's on

01:40:07.860 --> 01:40:11.730
the internet, people play, there are different rules.
That's amazing. The ones I invented are pretty

01:40:11.820 --> 01:40:15.400
much regular. So if you
have a good balance between

01:40:16.080 --> 01:40:20.019
chance and strategy and it's a fair game,

01:40:20.880 --> 01:40:24.700
and doesn't take four days to play like
modern board games. So you could have a

01:40:24.740 --> 01:40:28.700
go and if you're lucky, you win fast and
then you have another go, maybe best

01:40:28.719 --> 01:40:34.339
of three or something like that. It
works out rather well. And once I was in

01:40:35.460 --> 01:40:38.380
in California, in the

01:40:38.420 --> 01:40:42.339
Getty, and I had to give a talk about this with
all the information, and because there's lots of

01:40:42.360 --> 01:40:45.580
things to say about it.
And the lady who ran the

01:40:46.540 --> 01:40:50.299
Friends of the Getty had a brilliant
idea, so what she brought in

01:40:51.259 --> 01:40:55.219
20 or so commercial copies of this
game, and they had small tables with

01:40:55.259 --> 01:40:59.200
chairs. And after the lecture I was supposed
to say to everybody, "Okay, this is what

01:40:59.240 --> 01:41:03.219
you have to do, this is how you play." Because
you can get the rules down in like three minutes.

01:41:03.259 --> 01:41:07.000
So I said, "Okay, first you have to do
this, first you have to do that, so off you

01:41:07.040 --> 01:41:10.900
go." So there was silence,
and then after a while

01:41:11.259 --> 01:41:15.120
someone said, "I hate you!
I'm never playing this

01:41:15.160 --> 01:41:19.080
game with you again." When they'd
never played it before, when somebody

01:41:19.440 --> 01:41:23.379
had escaped at the last minute, cleaned
up just when they thought they were gonna

01:41:23.420 --> 01:41:30.690
get. And it provokes that salutary,

01:41:31.240 --> 01:41:34.740
which all good board games do. And
they were happily married couples who

01:41:34.759 --> 01:41:38.719
were, at the end of the afternoon, phoning
their respective lawyers to discuss the

01:41:38.780 --> 01:41:46.480
future, that kind of thing. Do you
think games are... our desire to play

01:41:46.599 --> 01:41:50.240
games, a mix of chance, a mix
of strategy, it's a part of

01:41:50.460 --> 01:41:56.900
human nature? Do you think that's
always been there? I do. I do, yes.

01:41:56.960 --> 01:42:00.719
I think, um... I mean, you can say that,

01:42:00.780 --> 01:42:04.610
In communities, you have
rivalry, hostility, and

01:42:04.679 --> 01:42:08.599
who's the best, who's the fastest, who's
the strongest and things. And if you play

01:42:08.679 --> 01:42:12.340
a board game like that, all the reality
of it is sublimated into a safe

01:42:12.460 --> 01:42:16.410
terrain. Yes, the safety of it, where you
can nevertheless get angry, but it's not

01:42:16.440 --> 01:42:20.299
like that. That's one thing. But
more significantly, I believe

01:42:20.400 --> 01:42:27.179
is the question of what in
India people call time pass.

01:42:27.219 --> 01:42:30.420
Mm-hmm. Which is not quite the same as past
time. Time pass is the question of what you

01:42:30.519 --> 01:42:34.490
time. Time pass is the
question of what you do when

01:42:34.500 --> 01:42:38.469
it's too hot to do anything,
which is true a good

01:42:38.519 --> 01:42:42.460
part of the day and a good part of
the year. And grandmothers sit under

01:42:42.540 --> 01:42:46.440
trees with their grandchildren and
they tell stories and they do this

01:42:46.480 --> 01:42:53.675
and they do that. And time pass is a very
useful catch-all phrase for the existence of

01:42:53.736 --> 01:43:01.036
board games. And in India, there are many
board games. Chess, of course, is the famous

01:43:01.116 --> 01:43:04.536
three-in-a-row type games or
fox-against- geese games, and

01:43:05.175 --> 01:43:09.076
wolves against sheep and all those sorts
of things which come out of the landscape

01:43:09.255 --> 01:43:12.556
in miniature and were
played for pleasure. And

01:43:12.656 --> 01:43:16.396
also in a kind of way, it doesn't really
matter who wins, because you might play

01:43:16.456 --> 01:43:20.276
matter who wins, because you might play
and it goes round and round and round,

01:43:20.335 --> 01:43:23.936
eventually somebody wins and then they
have another game. So it's a sort of

01:43:24.795 --> 01:43:28.776
that kind of rather
graceful, valid function for

01:43:28.835 --> 01:43:32.496
not wasting time, doing something
which is stimulating and

01:43:32.596 --> 01:43:40.366
beneficial without it being overpowering
in either way. So I think it is a human

01:43:40.896 --> 01:43:41.996
matter.

01:43:42.036 --> 01:43:45.776
- Of course, we humans also sometimes mix
in gambling into the whole thing, to

01:43:45.856 --> 01:43:49.516
mix in gambling into the whole thing, to
add some money on top of it, which I'm sure

01:43:50.016 --> 01:43:52.356
sometimes was involved here.

01:43:52.496 --> 01:43:57.876
- I think so, but probably only
late on, because money as such,

01:43:58.056 --> 01:44:05.116
of course, that doesn't appear till
quite late. But there are... We know in

01:44:05.135 --> 01:44:08.736
Mesopotamia, it's a rather interesting
thing, there's a school tablet

01:44:09.736 --> 01:44:13.656
with three or four lines quoted from
one literary thing and three or four

01:44:13.715 --> 01:44:19.866
from another literary thing.
And one of them, it has this

01:44:20.696 --> 01:44:27.135
"Oh my astragal, oh my
astragal, woe is me, woe is

01:44:27.215 --> 01:44:30.835
me." And that's all we have. And I think
this is an example of a genre of literature

01:44:30.956 --> 01:44:35.675
this is an example of a genre of
literature called the gambler's lament.

01:44:36.755 --> 01:44:40.736
Because they used knuckle bones
or astragals as dice. And

01:44:40.876 --> 01:44:44.166
I'm sure there were people
who bet a sack of this or

01:44:45.036 --> 01:44:48.385
a roomful of that on the throw
of the knuckle bones. And

01:44:48.456 --> 01:44:52.416
this extract in the school text is
probably from a literary tablet

01:44:52.456 --> 01:44:58.116
in which somebody lost everything,
even though there weren't

01:44:58.196 --> 01:45:01.596
coins, because I think you're
right that it's a natural-

01:45:02.236 --> 01:45:06.026
it's a natural thing for it to accrue. And
also maybe men and women played differently,

01:45:06.135 --> 01:45:10.016
also maybe men and women played
differently, because there are

01:45:10.056 --> 01:45:13.476
some games which were played in harems among
girls, you know, woman on a hot afternoon

01:45:13.916 --> 01:45:17.844
girls, you know, women on a hot
afternoon where nobody was gonna

01:45:17.876 --> 01:45:21.715
win anything. But the rules tablet, which

01:45:21.726 --> 01:45:25.715
gives this kind of backhanded
information about it,

01:45:25.795 --> 01:45:31.616
is couched in such a way that
it talks about people in a bar.

01:45:31.776 --> 01:45:35.635
Because the movement of the
pieces is calculated in terms of

01:45:36.896 --> 01:45:39.755
food and drink and women, what you win.

01:45:40.736 --> 01:45:44.684
So the landscape in which the
rules are couched for credibility

01:45:45.215 --> 01:45:49.576
are for just exactly that setup.

01:45:49.675 --> 01:45:51.125
- As you mentioned, you are

01:45:52.456 --> 01:45:57.135
the curator at possibly the greatest
place on Earth, the British Museum.

01:45:57.236 --> 01:45:58.335
- Oh, yes.

01:45:58.396 --> 01:46:02.096
- Can you tell me, what are some of
the incredible magical aspects

01:46:02.436 --> 01:46:03.596
of the British Museum?

01:46:04.376 --> 01:46:11.736
- Well, the British Museum is a magical
place, and it's a special case

01:46:11.755 --> 01:46:15.215
because there's a lot of flurry
and dispute now about what museums

01:46:15.556 --> 01:46:19.516
are, and what they're for, and why they exist,
and whether they should ever have existed,

01:46:19.576 --> 01:46:23.376
and all these sorts of issues
which people go on about. But the

01:46:23.396 --> 01:46:26.736
British Museum is unlike almost
all museums in the world,

01:46:27.215 --> 01:46:32.556
because it's to do with the achievements
of mankind from the beginning

01:46:32.876 --> 01:46:36.576
onwards. So it's a kind of celebration

01:46:36.696 --> 01:46:40.616
of art and more, but it's not
an art museum. It's to do

01:46:40.675 --> 01:46:44.356
with the struggle of the
human race against all the

01:46:44.396 --> 01:46:48.316
things that beset it and how it
has triumphed, and how marvelous

01:46:48.376 --> 01:46:52.316
it is and the things that have happened.
And not turning a blind eye to

01:46:52.356 --> 01:46:55.816
all the contrasting horrible things
that have happened. But it's the

01:46:55.896 --> 01:47:03.376
narrative of the human race, as I see
it, as discernible in objects. So it

01:47:03.456 --> 01:47:11.616
means that we serve two very important
horizons. One is that we represent, as far as

01:47:11.656 --> 01:47:18.456
we can, the whole world with no injudicious
attention paid to any one or other

01:47:18.536 --> 01:47:24.776
culture, that they're all to
us one. So there's no favoring

01:47:25.816 --> 01:47:29.476
any religious group, any
country group, anything of the

01:47:29.576 --> 01:47:33.295
kind. It's the human species. We try

01:47:33.376 --> 01:47:39.396
to tell the narrative of, in its
own right, and how it overlaps with

01:47:40.656 --> 01:47:44.616
its neighbors and what it's
learned from what came before.

01:47:44.715 --> 01:47:48.356
All those features together is
really what the concern of the

01:47:48.396 --> 01:47:52.226
museum is. And of course,
to collect everything

01:47:52.656 --> 01:47:55.776
we... or has been to collect
everything we can to tell those

01:47:55.835 --> 01:47:59.545
narratives, and also to look after them

01:47:59.616 --> 01:48:03.566
according to scientific
principle. So, all those things

01:48:03.576 --> 01:48:10.656
at once are the task for the British Museum.
And the second horizon it serves is the

01:48:10.736 --> 01:48:13.835
unborn. So,

01:48:14.956 --> 01:48:18.295
babies yet to be born, and their
children, and their children, and their

01:48:18.335 --> 01:48:22.175
children. And it seems to me that
the task of the museum is of such

01:48:22.635 --> 01:48:26.416
cultural significance and
such, so to speak, sacred

01:48:26.456 --> 01:48:30.236
validity, that it shouldn't
have to put up with

01:48:30.276 --> 01:48:33.976
people carping about
this or that or saying,

01:48:33.986 --> 01:48:37.726
"Museums are sinful and wicked
and should be demolished,"

01:48:37.795 --> 01:48:41.005
because the people who say these
things don't really have any

01:48:41.076 --> 01:48:46.795
idea of actually what it really does
stand for. And it's a kind of lighthouse

01:48:47.755 --> 01:48:54.585
in a universe where we are surrounded
by darkness, ignorance, stupidity,

01:48:54.585 --> 01:49:01.978
uninterest, disinterest, skepticism,
ignorance, and so forth.

01:49:02.448 --> 01:49:06.418
about the very issues that
we're interested in. And

01:49:06.428 --> 01:49:10.258
it's one of the places in the world
where you can talk about truth and

01:49:10.368 --> 01:49:14.348
beauty and elegance and
intelligence without

01:49:14.388 --> 01:49:18.208
it being an affront to people who have
none of those qualities, and without it

01:49:18.288 --> 01:49:21.948
being the kind of speech that people
shudder or they think you're being,

01:49:22.008 --> 01:49:25.808
Naive about it, because those
are the crucial things. And also

01:49:27.088 --> 01:49:30.478
about religion, that we don't
favor a religion and we don't

01:49:30.828 --> 01:49:36.148
sponsor a religion. We try to look at
them for what they are and to assess

01:49:37.288 --> 01:49:40.848
their relationships and what they offer.

01:49:40.888 --> 01:49:44.628
Perhaps with less acerbity
and less criticism

01:49:44.708 --> 01:49:48.488
than I would if I was the director,
I would try to put them down the

01:49:48.508 --> 01:49:52.318
wrong end of a microscope and look at
them for what they are and what they have

01:49:52.348 --> 01:49:56.178
done and what's been done in the name of
religion. You probably would never get

01:49:56.268 --> 01:50:00.067
away with that, but maybe one day
that will be an important part

01:50:00.088 --> 01:50:03.988
because it's a major contributive
factor to what's happened to the human

01:50:04.028 --> 01:50:06.888
race, which has never really articulated

01:50:07.668 --> 01:50:11.628
sharply about what religion
has done to us and where we

01:50:11.688 --> 01:50:15.628
might have been without it. Because not
having religion does not mean not having

01:50:15.748 --> 01:50:19.068
law or morality or sensitivity or

01:50:19.108 --> 01:50:23.048
consideration or love or any
of those things. None of those

01:50:23.068 --> 01:50:26.848
things depends on religion,
and those are the

01:50:26.888 --> 01:50:30.868
things which are important.
So I think it's people

01:50:30.928 --> 01:50:34.788
say, "Oh, you say this 'cause you work there
and you, you know, you're a curator, you

01:50:34.868 --> 01:50:38.648
wouldn't say that, that the British Museum is a
special place." It's nothing to do with that.

01:50:38.728 --> 01:50:42.568
It is actually a special place
because you cannot point

01:50:42.628 --> 01:50:46.468
to another museum in the
world with the same task.

01:50:46.768 --> 01:50:49.888
For example, the Louvre
is basically a museum of

01:50:51.008 --> 01:50:54.968
art, basically a museum of
art, not a museum of ideas.

01:50:54.988 --> 01:50:58.788
And the Met is definitely a museum of
art. It's called the Museum of Art

01:50:59.268 --> 01:51:02.568
and that's their priority.
Design and color and

01:51:02.608 --> 01:51:06.167
shape. To us, to my mind,
it's the British Museum.

01:51:06.387 --> 01:51:10.028
factor among many others. And we're
not an art museum and we're not a

01:51:10.088 --> 01:51:13.418
local museum, we're not a museum
of the history of the bicycle,

01:51:14.028 --> 01:51:17.908
we're not a celebration
of evil. We are, as it

01:51:17.968 --> 01:51:25.628
were, doing, as I see it, the best we
could do if, for example, a whole load of

01:51:25.688 --> 01:51:29.648
Martians arrived in the Great Court and

01:51:30.548 --> 01:51:34.517
burst through the front door
and said to us, "Tell us

01:51:34.648 --> 01:51:38.628
tell us all about this place. Tell us
about the world. Can you do it fast

01:51:38.648 --> 01:51:42.568
'cause we got to leave?" And if
you took them round and said,

01:51:42.588 --> 01:51:46.328
"Look at this, look at this, look at this,
look at this," they'd get some picture which

01:51:46.368 --> 01:51:50.318
wasn't insane. The only thing they
wouldn't get is a recording of

01:51:50.688 --> 01:51:54.428
Jonny B. Goode by Chuck Berry, but
apparently one's been put into

01:51:54.548 --> 01:51:58.048
space. Yeah. I've heard about it.
So this is a very comforting thing.

01:51:58.088 --> 01:52:02.017
- But that's kind of what... The task of the
British Museum is to do that but for the entirety

01:52:02.048 --> 01:52:02.928
of human history.

01:52:02.988 --> 01:52:03.578
- Yeah. It can be done.

01:52:03.578 --> 01:52:05.448
- It would be a store of artifacts-

01:52:05.628 --> 01:52:05.908
- Yes

01:52:06.588 --> 01:52:09.558
- ...that are the raindrops from which
you can reconstruct the waterfall.

01:52:09.568 --> 01:52:13.448
- Precisely so. And it's
not a valid criticism

01:52:13.508 --> 01:52:17.468
to say to us that most of the
stuff is not on exhibition, which

01:52:17.508 --> 01:52:20.848
is what everybody says. "It should go here,
it should go there 'cause it's not on

01:52:20.908 --> 01:52:27.488
exhibition." But we're not doing it for any
other reason than stockpiling for future

01:52:27.628 --> 01:52:31.358
examination. See, this is the important
perspective that nobody considers.

01:52:31.628 --> 01:52:35.487
Because the thing is, when you have
something which is contemporary,

01:52:35.568 --> 01:52:38.648
contemporary, if you're a clever

01:52:38.968 --> 01:52:42.808
journalist or a clever thinker, you can write
essays about it, you can talk about it,

01:52:42.888 --> 01:52:46.748
and you can see it, but you can only see it
from the perspective from which you operate.

01:52:46.788 --> 01:52:49.818
And with the passage of time, the
significance of objects, what they stand for,

01:52:49.948 --> 01:52:53.898
time, the significance of
objects, what they stand for,

01:52:53.928 --> 01:52:57.908
what they meant and what they can still
mean shifts. And the further back you go,

01:52:57.948 --> 01:53:01.797
the sharper you can understand things,
especially in terms of their own precedent

01:53:01.848 --> 01:53:05.548
and their own modern contemporary parallels.
So the benefit of distance, storage,

01:53:05.588 --> 01:53:13.888
and contemplation is
inestimable. Inestimable.

01:53:13.948 --> 01:53:18.408
- There are so many questions I want
to ask you. What wisdom do you think

01:53:20.308 --> 01:53:23.508
the people from whom
these artifacts came had,

01:53:24.488 --> 01:53:28.308
that we modern-day humans may have
lost or lost in part or in whole?

01:53:28.948 --> 01:53:32.908
So it's often, as you've spoken about, we
see the ancient peoples as lesser, dumber,

01:53:32.968 --> 01:53:40.478
more primitive. And you've spoken
about how they are basically the same.

01:53:40.908 --> 01:53:46.108
more primitive. And you've spoken
about how they are basically the same.

01:53:46.148 --> 01:53:50.028
- I think if you put them on a bus, all
wearing the same clothes, you wouldn't know.

01:53:50.628 --> 01:53:51.448
That's my feeling.

01:53:51.488 --> 01:53:55.168
- But there is some, I'm sure there's some
greater wisdom they had about certain things,

01:53:55.268 --> 01:53:59.348
as we have greater wisdom about
others. Thanks to Einstein,

01:54:00.748 --> 01:54:07.648
we've figured out the curvature of space-time.
Which they didn't know about. But...

01:54:07.668 --> 01:54:11.098
- They knew quite a lot about astronomy,
though. Quite a lot about astronomy.

01:54:11.108 --> 01:54:12.708
- They stared at the stars.

01:54:12.788 --> 01:54:16.728
- Yeah, and they measured them, and they made
calculations. And when the Greeks went to Babylon,

01:54:16.768 --> 01:54:19.728
they thought, "Hey man, this is really cool."
And they wrote it all down and went home.

01:54:19.768 --> 01:54:26.688
Yeah, definitely, definitely. Well, I
think it's a hard question to answer.

01:54:26.728 --> 01:54:30.648
I think it's, it's, it's a hard
question to answer. But one

01:54:30.708 --> 01:54:38.308
But one of the things is that they were spared things
which have cluttered up the essence of humanity.

01:54:38.368 --> 01:54:45.308
Because I think that the modern adherence to the
electronic universe is disastrous for humans,

01:54:45.348 --> 01:54:52.236
and because it reduces the
vitality of the human component.

01:54:52.396 --> 01:54:56.156
I think it's restrictive in a way that
people don't realize until it's too late.

01:54:56.216 --> 01:54:59.896
that people don't realize
until it's too late.

01:54:59.936 --> 01:55:03.716
Like drugs, if you take drugs now and again,
you think, "Oh, it's fine, it's fine."

01:55:03.756 --> 01:55:07.736
Then suddenly, you realize you're
addicted to heroin. It's a bit like that.

01:55:07.876 --> 01:55:11.616
People use the electronic world like an addictive
drug, and they can't get through without it.

01:55:11.675 --> 01:55:15.656
And I think this is a very recent thing.
But I suppose I'm not a Luddite and say,

01:55:15.696 --> 01:55:19.556
"We shouldn't have railway engines
and we shouldn't have kettles."

01:55:19.576 --> 01:55:25.876
But I think one of the things about the ancient
world was that people never went anywhere

01:55:25.936 --> 01:55:29.666
unless they were merchants or soldiers.
They never went anywhere. Probably people

01:55:29.976 --> 01:55:33.856
born and died in a village, and then their
children born and died in the village,

01:55:33.896 --> 01:55:37.496
and they never knew anything about
the outside world. Maybe very little.

01:55:37.576 --> 01:55:41.116
anything about the outside
world. Maybe a very little.

01:55:41.156 --> 01:55:45.116
about the outside world. Maybe a very little. Sometimes
there'd be a message, but in principle, they had

01:55:45.156 --> 01:55:47.296
no idea about other
countries, other languages,

01:55:48.175 --> 01:55:51.976
or how big they were or anything.
So I don't think they had wisdom

01:55:52.276 --> 01:55:55.736
in a way that you could type out
following precepts will make life better.

01:55:55.836 --> 01:56:03.236
Because they told lies, and they esteemed the truth,
and they fell in love, and they committed adultery,

01:56:03.476 --> 01:56:07.256
and they committed adultery, and they
did murder. They did all the things.

01:56:07.816 --> 01:56:11.796
I think in a way the ancient world allowed human
beings to behave more naturally than it does now.

01:56:11.856 --> 01:56:19.716
world allowed human beings to be- to behave more
naturally than it does now, the world in which we live.

01:56:19.796 --> 01:56:23.396
world in which we live. I mean, if you do live in a
rustic environment or by the sea, or you're a fisherman,

01:56:23.456 --> 01:56:27.376
in a rustic environment, or by the sea, or you're a fisherman,
or you... I mean, all those normal, real kind of things,

01:56:28.256 --> 01:56:32.096
normal, real kind of things, then it's probably all
right. But most people who live crammed in the cities

01:56:32.116 --> 01:56:35.675
But most people who live crammed in the
cities live a very, very artificial life

01:56:35.756 --> 01:56:39.696
artificial life, where the principles, which they regard
as ineluctably crucial, are not ineluctably crucial.

01:56:39.796 --> 01:56:43.576
crucial are not ineluctably crucial. They're not in...
You know, one example is this ghastly thing on mobiles.

01:56:43.716 --> 01:56:47.056
You know, one example is this ghastly thing on mobiles,
where you get a short clip from a real program.

01:56:47.675 --> 01:56:50.806
where you get a short
clip from a real program.

01:56:50.936 --> 01:56:54.776
I think it's utterly, utterly wicked.
So you have children all over the world

01:56:54.856 --> 01:57:02.316
who cannot articulate, spell, or make meaning clear,
using the best, most literary, and most beneficial

01:57:02.376 --> 01:57:06.056
most literary, and most beneficial language
that's ever been created, which is English.

01:57:06.135 --> 01:57:14.076
They have to save their lives, and they
use a word... I'll give you an example.

01:57:14.156 --> 01:57:16.736
Right? Like, "I went."

01:57:16.836 --> 01:57:17.476
- Like I went.

01:57:17.536 --> 01:57:18.546
- Like I went.

01:57:18.546 --> 01:57:22.536
So difficult to define that grammatically.
Difficult. Like, "I should have gone,"

01:57:22.635 --> 01:57:26.385
I should have gone. Where "I went" or
"I should have gone" means to speak.

01:57:26.436 --> 01:57:30.096
gone means to speak. Now, how would it be
if when we see the verb "to go" in Sumerian

01:57:30.156 --> 01:57:34.056
be if when we see the verb "to go" in
Sumerian, it actually meant to speak?

01:57:34.156 --> 01:57:39.496
actually meant to speak? How... Where
would we be? Where would we be?

01:57:39.566 --> 01:57:43.106
- I mean, we should probably say that even at
that time, there was probably slang, right?

01:57:43.135 --> 01:57:45.986
there was probably slang, right?
It just wouldn't end up written.

01:57:45.986 --> 01:57:49.936
- Yes, there were dialects. There were words that
sailors used. For sure, all those things--

01:57:50.016 --> 01:57:50.496
things.

01:57:50.516 --> 01:57:52.656
- But they wouldn't end up in writing.

01:57:52.736 --> 01:57:53.635
- Sometimes they do.

01:57:53.656 --> 01:57:57.576
- We have to remember that Cambridge and Oxford
speak in a certain way that's proper and formal

01:57:57.616 --> 01:58:04.316
and very smart, but there's most of the people in
bars. Sailors have a different way of speaking.

01:58:04.496 --> 01:58:06.596
sailors have a different way of speaking.

01:58:06.656 --> 01:58:06.696
- They do.

01:58:06.716 --> 01:58:12.576
- So they would probably say, "Like,
I went," and have emojis, and...

01:58:13.316 --> 01:58:16.866
- But the thing is, you have to
moderate your vocabulary--

01:58:16.866 --> 01:58:20.696
if you talk to people of a certain age, because
they don't know what the f*** you're talking about,

01:58:20.736 --> 01:58:24.616
you're talking about, if you use language exactly. And
the thing that was just so exquisite about English

01:58:24.656 --> 01:58:28.336
exquisite about English is, like with a barrister,
you can make a case which is absolutely wonderful

01:58:28.396 --> 01:58:32.346
you can make a case which is absolutely
wonderful, because it says exactly what it means,

01:58:32.476 --> 01:58:36.126
because it says exactly what it means, and
there's no wiggle room. And the conversation

01:58:36.156 --> 01:58:40.096
it... The conversation should be like that, with no
wiggle room. It's not just a matter of spelling,

01:58:40.135 --> 01:58:44.116
not just a matter of spelling, but the
basic vocabulary. You know, something...

01:58:44.156 --> 01:58:48.116
You know something very interesting, people
say they know English or they speak English.

01:58:48.135 --> 01:58:52.096
Have you ever in your life
opened a full-size volume of

01:58:52.135 --> 01:58:55.916
the Oxford English Dictionary?
It's about that thick. I have a

01:58:55.956 --> 01:58:59.786
whole set. I love them. So this
is it, you take a volume off the

01:58:59.876 --> 01:59:03.436
shelf and you open the
book and you run your

01:59:03.496 --> 01:59:07.456
forefinger down the various columns
of writing. You might have to turn

01:59:07.536 --> 01:59:11.436
